<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Marine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corps </ORGANIZATION> on Sunday released the names of the seven Marines killed Saturday in a helicopter crash in <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>. The CH-53D chopper crashed on <LOCATION> Shikoku </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION> during a routine flight from the <ORGANIZATION> Marines </ORGANIZATION>' air station at <LOCATION> Iwikuni </LOCATION> to another corps air station at <LOCATION> Futenma </LOCATION>, where the craft was based. A <ORGANIZATION> Marine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corps </ORGANIZATION> spokeswoman, Lt. <PERSON> Elizabeth </PERSON> <PERSON> Kerstens </PERSON>, said the cause of the accident was under investigation. The victims, who were members of <ORGANIZATION> Heavy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Helicopter </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Squadron </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> 462 </ORGANIZATION>, were based at the <ORGANIZATION> Marine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corps </ORGANIZATION> air station at <LOCATION> Tustin </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif. </LOCATION>, and on a six-month assignment in <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Kerstens </PERSON> said. The seven were identified as Capt. <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Bermel </PERSON>, <PERSON> Cataldo </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Idaho </LOCATION>; 1st Lt. <PERSON> Patrick </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Fleming </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Bay </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mich. </LOCATION>; Staff Sgt. <PERSON> Stephen </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> Yoder </PERSON>, <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bernardino </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif. </LOCATION>; Sgt. <PERSON> Eric </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Mau </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Bakersfield </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif. </LOCATION>; Sgt. <PERSON> Donald </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> McKay </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Westlake </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION>; Sgt. <PERSON> Jay </PERSON> <PERS