<HEAD>Two Sides Reach Agreement on Territory's Future</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The head of <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Caledonia </LOCATION>'s separatist movement and the islands' conservative pro-French deputy reached agreement early Sunday on the future of the troubled territory, Prime Minister <PERSON> Michel </PERSON> <PERSON> Rocard </PERSON> announced. He said that under the accord, <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION> will assume direct control of the <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Pacific </LOCATION> territory for the next 12 months, with <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Caledonians </LOCATION> voting in referendum in 10 years on the issue of self-determination. <PERSON> Rocard </PERSON> also said he would propose to President <PERSON> Francois </PERSON> <PERSON> Mitterrand </PERSON> that the French people be consulted in a referendum on new institutions to be set up to develop the territory. Tensions in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Caledonia </LOCATION>, an island group 1,000 miles east of <LOCATION> Australia </LOCATION>, have remained high 21 people were killed in May when a French army assault team stormed a cave to free 23 hostages held by native Melanesian separatists. Thirty people have died in violence in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Caledonia </LOCATION> since April 22. The accord reached Sunday came after negotations in <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION> involving <PERSON> Rocard </PERSON>, <PERSON> Jean-Marie </PERSON> <PERSON> Tjibaou </PERSON>, head of the <ORGANIZATION> Kanak </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Socialist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Front </ORGANIZATION>, and deputy <PERSON> Jacques </PERSON> <PERSON> LaFleur </PERSON>. The Kanaks, or Melanesians, represent about 43 percent of the <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Caledonia </LOCATION>'s 145,000 residents, and most favor independence. The rest of the population comprises descendents of European settlers, Asians and Polynesians, most of whom prefer to remain French. <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> colonized the islands in 1853. <PERSON> Rocard </PERSON> brought <PERSON> Tjibaou </PERSON> and <PERSON> LaFleur </PERSON> together last week for their first meeting since 1982. He said they both would take the agreement to their respective constituencies and call for approval. Tjibaou called the agreement reached Sunday `` an important step'' but said the <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Caledonia </LOCATION> problem has not been solved and native Melanesians will continue to demand independence. He said the talks were difficult because the demands of the two sides were contradictory and because of the tense atmosphere in the territory. `` Each side now is committed to halt bloodshed and end mourning for many families, `` Tjibaou said. A statement issued by <PERSON> Rocard </PERSON> called on the territory's inhabitants to `` be hopeful for a new page has been turned, not by arms but by dialogue and tolerance, by hard work and good will. <PERSON> Rocard </PERSON> made a solution to the <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Caledonia </LOCATION> problem a priority after <PERSON> Mitterrand </PERSON> named him prime minister 45 days ago. The agreement seems likely to restore some of <PERSON> Rocard </PERSON>'s prestige, which was tarnished after the Socialists failed to win a majority in legislative elections that followed the May 8 presidential vote.
</TEXT>
