<HEAD>New Jet Crashes During Air Show; At Least Three Dead</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 8 grafs to UPDATE with pilot telling newspaper he
could not increase power. Picks up 7th graf pvs, `A woman ... </NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto PAR9</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MULHOUSE, France (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A new <ORGANIZATION> Airbus </ORGANIZATION> jetliner carrying more than 130 people crashed into a forest Sunday during an air show demonstration flight, killing at least three people and injuring 98, officials said. Many victims were believed to be first-time fliers who paid for a ride on the twin-engine <ORGANIZATION> Airbus </ORGANIZATION> A320, which was delivered to <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> France </ORGANIZATION> only Thursday. Witnesses said the plane, which touts a state-of-the-art electronic flight system, had just passed over the airfield hosting the show when it crashed, tearing a nearly 500-foot path through the woods. Part of the plane caught fire. A control tower official said the jet appeared to lose power as it passed over the field in <LOCATION> Habsheim </LOCATION>, a village about 15 miles from the Swiss border. Monday's editions of the <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION> daily newspaper L'Humanite quoted the jet's pilot as telling a rescue worker: `` I wanted to to increase the power but the aircraft did not respond.'' `` It was about 20 meters -LRB- 65 feet -RRB- above the ground with its flaps and landing gear down when it clipped some trees at the end of the runway and crashed in the forest,'' <PERSON> Bernard </PERSON> <PERSON> Labalette </PERSON>, an amateur pilot, was quoted by <PERSON> Agence </PERSON> <PERSON> France-Presse </PERSON> as saying. Visibility was perfect. A 25-year-old woman passenger who did not give her name was quoted by AFP as saying she heard trees brush against the fuselage. `` From then on things went fast,'' she said. `` The plane hit the ground hard and we had the feeling of an abrupt jolt. Then there was a fire in the front of the aircraft.'' Flight attendants deployed evacuation chutes and the woman said she and other passengers slid down and ran away, fearing an explosion. Rescuers worked throughout the afternoon to evacuate dozens of people trapped in the battered plane. The impact broke the plane's wings and smashed the cockpit windows The fuselage was blackened from smoke, <ORGANIZATION> AFP </ORGANIZATION> said. Local officials said 50 people were hospitalized. It was not clear how many were on the jet as there was no official passenger list. Authorities said at least 136 were aboard. Officials said the pilot, <PERSON> Michel </PERSON> <PERSON> Asseline </PERSON>, and the co-pilot, <PERSON> Pierre </PERSON> <PERSON> Mazieres </PERSON>, were not injured. Initial reports said four people were killed. The local officials, not named in accordance with <LOCATION> French </LOCATION> practice, later said they were able to confirm three deaths. They said some victims were badly burned. `` There was an explosion and a cloud of smoke. But from the control tower we could n't see,'' said the tower official, who did not give his name. He said about 1,000 people were at the show and that many on the plane were making their first flight. At such air shows, spectators are invited to participate in an `` air baptism,'' or take their first flight for a small fee. The plane made six flights on Saturday. The A320, built in <LOCATION> Toulouse </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> by a European consortium, went into service in April for <LOCATION> Air </LOCATION> <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> and <ORGANIZATION> British </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airways </ORGANIZATION>. It was conceived and certified for flight by a two-member crew, eliminating the navigator. Early this year, pilots and flight engineers of <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inter </ORGANIZATION>, the largest French airline, called a series of strikes to protest the use of only two cockpit members in A320s, saying it was unsafe. In <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, <ORGANIZATION> British </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airways </ORGANIZATION> suspended service on its two A320 aircraft as a precautionary measure pending information on the cause of the accident in <LOCATION> Habsheim </LOCATION>, which is just outside <LOCATION> Mulhouse </LOCATION> and 250 miles east of <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION>. Air <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> President <PERSON> Jacques </PERSON> <PERSON> Friedman </PERSON> said that as a precaution, the airline was replacing an A320 due to fly to <LOCATION> Dusseldorf </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Berlin </LOCATION> on Sunday night with a <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> 737 and canceling a Paris-Zurich flight. French Transport Minister <PERSON> Louis </PERSON> <PERSON> Mermez </PERSON> said a commission of inquiry would begin work Monday. The Airbus A320 can carry 168 passengers. Airbus Indusrie, its manufacturer, has orders to purchase 500 of the craft. Minneapolis-based <ORGANIZATION> Northwest </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> agreed to buy some of the A320s for delivery in 1990 and 1991. `` I doubt -LRB- the crash -RRB- would have an impact on our decision to purchase from <ORGANIZATION> Airbus </ORGANIZATION>,'' <PERSON> Alan </PERSON> <PERSON> Muncaster </PERSON>, staff vice president of corporate communications for <ORGANIZATION> Northwest </ORGANIZATION>, said Sunday. `` But obviously we would want to check into the cause of the crash.'' Air <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> has three of the aircraft, <ORGANIZATION> British </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airways </ORGANIZATION> has two and <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inter </ORGANIZATION>, the French domestic airline, has one, <ORGANIZATION> Airbus </ORGANIZATION> said. `` We are disturbed, shocked and saddened,'' said <ORGANIZATION> Airbus </ORGANIZATION> press spokesman <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Alizart </PERSON> in <LOCATION> Toulouse </LOCATION>. He said it was the first crash of an A320. <PERSON> Alizart </PERSON> said it was too early to say whether the future of the aircraft, which received its certification Feb. 26, could be in doubt. The plane has a range of about 3,700 miles and consumes 40 percent less fuel than similar two or three engine jets. It is the first civilian airliner equipped with a fully computerized flight-control system the manufacturer says permits safer, electronically controlled flight. Instead of the old control column in front of the pilot, there is a `` pistol-grip'' side stick linked to five computers that modify and relay the pilot's directions to wing and tail flaps
</TEXT>
