<FIRST>r i PM-WorldDrought     06-26 0771</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-World Drought,0793</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S. Drought Could Cause Severe Drop In World Grain Stocks</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also in Monday AMs report.</NOTE>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEPHEN R. WILSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ROME (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Worldwide grain stocks could sink to their lowest levels of the decade and lead to possible food shortages if the crippling <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> drought continues for another two weeks, according to a <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> organization. But officials at the <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Food </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION> say favorable weather and crop prospects have created a brighter farm picture in most of the rest of the world. Before the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> drought took hold, the Rome-based <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> organization already was projecting that world grain production in 1988-89 would not match consumption and that stocks would drop close to the level the agency considers the minimum necessary to safeguard world food security. `` Now with the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> drought, the question is how much is <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> production going to be drawn down,'' <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> Newhouse </PERSON>, chief of the agency's global information and early warning service, said in an interview Friday. `` It's still too early for firm projections. It all depends on the rain in the next two weeks,'' he said. The organization had projected June that the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> would produce 279 million tons of this year's targeted 1.67 billion tons of grain worldwide. But that was before the worst drought since the Great Depression parched the <LOCATION> Midwest </LOCATION>. `` If the present dry weather were to continue over the next couple of weeks, then there would be a severe shortfall in <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> crops, particularly maize -LRB- corn -RRB-,'' <PERSON> Newhouse </PERSON> said. `` We had already projected that with normal weather conditions, the stocks could fall close to the minimum level. Now if the drought continues, there's a distinct possibility it could fall below that.'' The <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> organization considers the minimum level to be 17 percent to 18 percent of the projected global consumption of wheat for the following year. The last time the level fell to the minimum level was in 1981. Stocks have not dropped below the minimum since the mid-1970s. They hit a low of 14 percent during the global food crisis of 1972-73. `` If stocks go below the mininum level, it would mean the world is more vulnerable than it should be and could face food supply difficulties,'' <PERSON> Newhouse </PERSON> said. `` We've still got a cushion ... but if the cushion is going to be used up, it looks like the food situation on a global level is going to be a lot tighter.'' <PERSON> Newhouse </PERSON> said the organization `` will have to be very vigilant'' in monitoring <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> cereal crops and those in <LOCATION> Asia </LOCATION>, the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>. `` Fortunately, harvest prospects outside the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION> are generally favorable,'' <PERSON> Newhouse </PERSON> said. `` At this moment, we do n't see any widespread drought problems... nothing dramatic,'' said <PERSON> Rene </PERSON> <PERSON> Gommes </PERSON> of the agency's agro-meteorological The only country that produces more cereal crops than the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> is <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> with about 350 million tons annually. Third is the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> with 200 million tons. <PERSON> Newhouse </PERSON> said harvest prospects were good in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>. In <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>, drought has hit some areas and floods have hit others. `` But at this point we're not worried about <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>,'' he said. An important factor for world crop production is the monsoon season in <LOCATION> India </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Bangladesh </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION>, which were hit by severe drought last year. `` The monsoon started in May on time this year, but it's still far too early to say what will happen,'' <PERSON> Newhouse </PERSON> said. One of the world's most serious food supply situations is occurring partly as a result of heavy rainfall in areas often prone to drought conditions. Swarms of migrating desert locusts, who breed in rainy conditions, have invaded the <LOCATION> Sahel </LOCATION> region of sub-Saharan <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>. The infestation `` is of unprecedented dimensions and will affect the food security of 15 African countries, from the <LOCATION> Atlantic </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ocean </LOCATION> to the <LOCATION> Red </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Sea </LOCATION>,'' the <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> group's director-general, <PERSON> Edouard </PERSON> <PERSON> Saouma </PERSON>, said Friday. In African countries such as <LOCATION> Angola </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mozambique </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Sudan </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Ethiopia </LOCATION>, civil war has aggravated crop failures. In <LOCATION> Ethiopia </LOCATION>, where drought and famine killed up to 1 million people in 1984-85, more than 7 million people are reported threatened by the drought and last year's crop failures. The crop planting season is now under way in <LOCATION> Ethiopia </LOCATION> so it wo n't be known until the end of the year whether the country can recover, <ORGANIZATION> Newhouse </ORGANIZATION> said. In <LOCATION> Latin </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>, northeast <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION> suffered severe drought last year but the weather has improved and <ORGANIZATION> Newhouse </ORGANIZATION> believes the harvest will recover. <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>, however, is expecting a shortfall of more than 1 million tons in its wheat harvest, he said.
</TEXT>
