<HEAD>Bomb Explodes In Front Of Singleton's Home, Police Say</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TAMPA, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A small bomb was hurled at the home listed as the address of rapist-mutilator <PERSON> Lawrence </PERSON> <PERSON> Singleton </PERSON> on Saturday night, but the explosion caused no injuries or property damage, authorities said. The homemade bomb detonated in the front yard of the one-story home just before 9 p.m., said <LOCATION> Hillsborough </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> Sheriff's Lt. <PERSON> Ken </PERSON> <PERSON> Allen </PERSON>. `` <PERSON> Lawrence </PERSON> <PERSON> Singleton </PERSON> was not in the house, his whereabouts are still unknown at this time,'' <PERSON> Allen </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Singleton </PERSON>'s brother, <PERSON> Walter </PERSON>, and sister-in-law, <PERSON> Diane </PERSON>, were the only people in the home when the device exploded, leaving a heavy white cloud, the officer said. While many in the quiet <LOCATION> Forest </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hills </LOCATION> neighborhood heard the explosion, there were no witnesses to who threw the device, <PERSON> Allen </PERSON> said. Experts were examining bomb shards to determine what type of device it was. <PERSON> Singleton </PERSON> was convicted of raping a 15-year-old hitchhiker, chopping her arms off with an ax and leaving her for dead in a ditch southeast of <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION> in 1978. The gray-bearded 60-year-old former merchant seaman, who grew up in <LOCATION> Tampa </LOCATION>, spent eight years of a 14-year sentence in a <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> prison. He completed a year-long probation and is now a free man. During his probation, <PERSON> Singleton </PERSON> was forced to flee six <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> towns after residents objected to his presence. He ended up finishing his probation in a trailer on the grounds of <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Quentin </LOCATION> prison. Two weeks ago, he listed the address with authorities as required of convicted felons under state law, but he has never been seen there. His brother has said <PERSON> Singleton </PERSON> lives `` about two hours away,'' but refuses to say exactly where. Angry area residents have held two meetings in the past month asking deputies to locate <PERSON> Singleton </PERSON> so they can stop living in fear. A local businessman and a radio station have each offered <PERSON> Singleton </PERSON> $ 5,000 if he will pack up and go anywhere else.
