details of crash; picks up 3rd graf pvs: An official...</NOTE>
<DATELINE>MULHOUSE, France (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 An Airbus A320 jetliner carrying 127 people crashed during an air show in eastern <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>, killing at least two people and injuring 60, district government officials said. Witnesses said the <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> France </ORGANIZATION> jet, which went into service a month ago, clipped some trees at the edge of an airport runway and crashed in a field nearby. An unidentified passenger, a 25-year-old woman, was quoted by <PERSON> Agence </PERSON> <PERSON> France-Presse </PERSON> as saying that she heard she heard tree branches rub against the plane's fuselage. `` Things started moving fast,'' she said. `` The plane hit the ground hard and we had the feeling of a abrupt jolt. Then there was a fire in the front of the aircraft.'' She was quoted as saying that the plane's evacuation chutes were deployed and many passengers aboard slid down and got off, running a distance from the plane because they feared an explosion. The twin-engine jet was taking part in an air show in overcast, humid weather. An official at the <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Transport </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION> said the accident occurred at 2:50 p.m. -LRB- 8:50 a.m. EDT -RRB- while the plane was on a low-altitude demonstration flight above the Mulhouse-Habsheim airport. He spoke on condition of anonymity. Medical evacuation helicopters and ambulances rushed to the airport, located about 18 miles north of the <LOCATION> Swiss </LOCATION> city of Bale. The new twin-engine plane can carry 163 people. It features a fully computerized flight-control system and went into service last month with <LOCATION> Air </LOCATION> <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> and <ORGANIZATION> British </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airways </ORGANIZATION>. The plane is manufactured by <ORGANIZATION> Airbus </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Industrie </ORGANIZATION>, a consortium of European aircraft compan