<HEAD>Pakistani Foreign Minister's Car In Accident</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The car carrying Pakistani Foreign Minister <PERSON> Sahabzada </PERSON> <PERSON> Yaqub-Khan </PERSON> crashed into the back of a Jeep on Sunday and slightly injured a Chinese woman, Pakistani officials said. <PERSON> Yaqub-Khan </PERSON> expressed regret over the accident and concern for the woman when he met later with Chinese Foreign Minister <PERSON> Qian </PERSON> <PERSON> Qichen </PERSON>. <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION> Embassy official <PERSON> Nisarullah </PERSON> <PERSON> Baluch </PERSON> said the jeep was ahead of the foreign minister's convoy, which was driving from the airport. The Jeep's driver misunderstood police signals to pull over and instead stopped, and the foreign minister's car struck it in the rear. A woman who was sitting in the back of the open-ended vehicle fell out, <PERSON> Baluch </PERSON> said. He said she was taken to a hospital with a slight head injury. <PERSON> Yaqub-Khan </PERSON> is the first Pakistani official to visit <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> since <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION>'s President <PERSON> Mohammad </PERSON> <PERSON> Zia </PERSON> <PERSON> Ul-haq </PERSON> abruptly dissolved the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Assembly </ORGANIZATION> and dismissed Prime Minister <PERSON> Mohammad </PERSON> <PERSON> Khan </PERSON> <PERSON> Junejo </PERSON> and other ministers on May 29. <PERSON> Zia </PERSON> acted just as <PERSON> Junejo </PERSON> returned home from a trip to <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Yaqub-Khan </PERSON>, who resigned as foreign minister last year for personal reasons, has resumed the post in a caretaker government pending elections. In a speech prepared for delivery at a welcome banquet given by <PERSON> Qian </PERSON>, he said the fact that his first visit in office was to <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> showed the `` exception relationship'' between the two countries. <PERSON> Yaqub-Khan </PERSON> is scheduled to meet Monday with Chinese Premier <PERSON> Li </PERSON> <PERSON