<HEAD>Pontiff Reaches Out to Eastern Europe's Catholics</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Pope, Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KEVIN COSTELLOE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Pope <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> II </PERSON> has used his Austrian tour to reach out to those nearby Roman Catholics whose Eastern bloc countries he has not been able to visit. While most attention on the five-day trip has focused on the pope's remarks about Jews and the Holocaust, <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> has also been looking to millions of Catholics in <LOCATION> Yugoslavia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Czechoslovakia </LOCATION>. On Saturday, about 20,000 Yugoslav Catholics crossed the border to the nearby Austrian town of <LOCATION> Gurk </LOCATION> for an outdoor Mass. The day before, the pope said Mass for 80,000 Catholics, mostly Yugoslavs and Hungarians, in the town of <LOCATION> Trausdorf </LOCATION> near the Hungarian border. The pope has visited <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>, his Communist homeland, three times since he became head of the <ORGANIZATION> Roman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION> in 1978. But so far, Communist governments have imposed barriers that have kept him from visiting millions of Catholics in <LOCATION> Czechoslovakia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Yugoslavia </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>. Czechoslovak Catholics in particular have been in conflict with Communist authorities, who until this year had not permitted any new bishops in their country since 1973. Earlier this month, <LOCATION> Prague </LOCATION> authorities finally allowed three new ones. The estimated 20,000 Yugoslav Catholics joined about 40,000 Italians and Austrians for the outdoor Mass on Saturday in <LOCATION> Gurk </LOCATION>. `` You all give testimony of the power of Christian faith to overcome boundaries,'' <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> said. `` Coming from several cultures, you as the people of God speak the one language of common belief.'' `` Unfortunately today in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>, even in your regions, the ancient roots of faith are threatened in various ways,'' the pontiff said, changing briefly from German to Italian in his homily. He continued: `` Christians must, however, react as a community to this challenge. They must unite even more and stay even closer together.'' On Friday, he said his Mass for the 80,000 Catholics, mostly Yugoslavs and Hungarians, in <LOCATION> Trausdorf </LOCATION>. Several hundred Poles and several dozen Czechs also were on hand. Addressing the local Austrian Catholics, the pontiff said: `` This diocese and its bishop are well aware of their function as a link in particular with the peoples of <LOCATION> Eastern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>.'' `` You are ready to cultivate contacts with them and to share with them, materially and spiritually,'' he said. `` Must not the salvation <PERSON> Christ </PERSON> has given us again be spread to the farthest bounds of <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>?'' Some Austrian newspapers hailed the Mass as a major gesture toward Eastern <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>. `` Trausdorf: A Signal for the East Bloc,'' trumpeted <LOCATION> Vienna </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Kleine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Zeitung </ORGANIZATION> daily newspaper in its Saturday editions Other newspapers, though, felt that the pontiff had kept his remarks deliberately low-key, possibly in hope of not upsetting any chances he may have of visiting any new Eastern European countries. `` He overcame barriers by not putting up any,'' said the conservative Die Presse daily newspaper of <LOCATION> Vienna </LOCATION>.
