<SECOND>AM-Dukakis-Furlough, Bjt,880</SECOND>
<HEAD>Massachusetts Furlough Program At Center Of Dukakis-Bush Crime
Debate</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 As Republican <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> wages an aggressive effort to portray <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> as a liberal who is soft on crime, the man at the center of the vice president's pitch is behind bars in a <LOCATION> Maryland </LOCATION> prison. Convicted murderer and rapist <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Horton </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON> is as much a part of the debate over crime this presidential campaign season as the opposite views on the death penalty espoused by the two candidates. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> now mentions <PERSON> Horton </PERSON> by name, in campaign rhetoric laced with attacks on a <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> furlough program that allowed <PERSON> Horton </PERSON> to be released from prison although he was serving a life sentence for murdering a 17-year-old boy. In 1987, during his 10th furlough, <PERSON> Horton </PERSON> fled to <LOCATION> Maryland </LOCATION>, twice raped a woman and assaulted her fiance. `` I think Governor <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> owes the people of the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> an explanation,'' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said last week in <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION>. `` What did the Democratic governor of <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> think he was doing when he let convicted first-degree murderers out on weekend passes?'' A day earlier, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> was told of <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>' statement that 45 states and the federal prison system offer some form of furlough. The vice president responded that `` none, except <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION>, had furlough programs for first-degree murderers.'' But, according to several correctional associations and publications, at least 16 states offer furloughs to first-degree murderers. <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> no longer is among them: <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> reluctantly signed a law banning first-degree lifers from furloughs. `` <PERSON> Ralph </PERSON> <PERSON> Waldo </PERSON> <PERSON> Emerson </PERSON> said that foolish consistency is the hobgoblin of little minds,'' <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> said when he signed the bill in April. `` I try to listen; I try to learn.'' Since the <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> program began in 1972, 117,700 furloughs were granted to 10,553 inmates. Of the 426 escapes, 11 occurred during the 4,908 furloughs granted to first-degree murderers. `` <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> actually had a pretty good record,'' said <PERSON> Brian </PERSON> <PERSON> Bemus </PERSON>, a researcher at the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corrections </ORGANIZATION> data center in <LOCATION> Boulder </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Colo. </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> has amended his attack on the furlough program, accurately saying in recent days that <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION>, until April, had the only furlough program in the nation for inmates sentenced to life without parole Campaign aides say the vice president will continue his attack. `` He finds this program of furloughing murderers with no-parole sentences represents the worst sort of approach to crime,'' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> spokeswoman <PERSON> Alixe </PERSON> <PERSON> Glen </PERSON> said Friday. `` The furlough issue is important because it shows how <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>' record on crime contrasts with the vice president's positions. As this issue has been elevated, I think the <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> people are shocked at the <PERSON> Willie </PERSON> <PERSON> Horton </PERSON> example.'' Faced with growing criticism from <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> and increased media attention on the furlough program, the <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> camp has fired back with national furlough statistics showing the <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> furlough-escape rate is below average and by invoking the name of <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s boss, President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>, who as governor of <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> supported furloughs even after two convicts killed people while on furlough in the early 1970s. Like <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>, <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> inherited the furlough program from a governor of the opposition party. `` These are part and parcel of all kinds of responsible correction programs,'' says <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>, who has spent much of the past week defending the <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> program, largely by citing a 14 percent drop in crime in his state over the past five years. `` Our view is that the vice president is trying, through the furlough issue, to obscure the facts,'' <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> issues adviser <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> Herman </PERSON> said in an interview. `` The fact is that while crime is going up nationally, crime is dropping dramatically in <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION>. `` He also is using it to obscure the unenviable crimefighting record of the Reagan-Bush administration,'' said <PERSON> Herman </PERSON>, who spent much of last week researching furlough programs. `` <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> is reacting to this issue in a sense that tells me he's running scared.'' If the criticisms continue, aides say, look for <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> to adopt the strategy he used when former rival Sen. <PERSON> Albert </PERSON> <PERSON> Gore </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Tennessee </LOCATION> criticized the <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> furlough program during the primary campaign. `` Al, the difference between you and me is that I have to run a criminal justice system. You never have,'' <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> said during an April debate in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. That kind of response to <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> would fit in with the <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> strategy to attempt to characterize <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> as a do-nothing vice president. Among corrections officials and criminoligists, furloughs are considered an effective rehabilitation tool. `` Most knowledgeable correctional workers, prisoners and others interested in work furlough see it as a progressive correctional program,'' said a 1975 review of one program _ that of then-California Gov. <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>. `` There is no way that we're ever going to be 100 percent able to give you a program where the parole board or the furlough program has fallen down,'' said Professor <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Fox </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> Northeastern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Criminal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION>. He also questioned the relevance of the furlough issue in presidential politics. `` If freeing a murderer on furlough is the issue, then it's moot because murder is, except for in rare cases, a state crime and the president does n't really deal with murderers,'' <PERSON> Fox </PERSON> said.
