<HEAD>Pentagon Doesn't Expect Immediate Slowdown in Contract Awards</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NORMAN BLACK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Military Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The defense industry fears that the investigation of fraud and bribery in <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> contracting will cause a slowdown in contract awards and new layers of oversight, but the <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> says it does n't expect that fallout any time soon. `` We are at least weeks, if not months, away from the kind of evidence which would point to looking at the acquisition process -LRB- for an overhaul -RRB-,'' says <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Howard </PERSON>, the <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION>'s chief spokesman. In the meantime, the process of awarding contracts `` has not ground to a halt,'' <PERSON> Howard </PERSON> said. `` It could n't if we continue to stay in business.'' However, industry officials were nearly unanimous in their concern about the impact of the probe. The investigation `` is very bad news for all of us because of the effect it's going to have on the reputation of the industry in total, and because of the stimulus it will provide for additional regulations and oversight,'' <PERSON> W. </PERSON> <PERSON> B. </PERSON> <PERSON> Jones </PERSON>, a vice president of the <ORGANIZATION> Grumman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, said last week. `` We'll get regulations and stipulations on what consultants may do,'' said <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> Campbell </PERSON>, an aerospace analyst for the <ORGANIZATION> Paine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Webber </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Larry </PERSON> <PERSON> McCracken </PERSON>, manager of media relations for <ORGANIZATION> Raytheon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, said, `` Most people believe the procurement process will probably slow down a bit because of new people being moved into some of the positions -LRB- at the Pentagon -RRB- The whole process,'' <PERSON> McCracken </PERSON> said, `` will just be a more cautious process.'' Several companies are also worried that existing contracts will be canceled because of evidence of wrongdoing and `` they may have to rebid projects already under way,'' said <PERSON> Herbert </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Hetu </PERSON>, a spokesman for the <ORGANIZATION> Aerospace </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Industries </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>. Former <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> Secretary <PERSON> Caspar </PERSON> <PERSON> Weinberger </PERSON>, meanwhile, said Sunday that an earlier study of <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> contracting found that contractors already are overaudited and often do n't have the opportunity to make adequate profits. And he expressed a fear that the scandal could lead to cuts in defense spending. `` I certainly hope that this is not used as an excuse by the professional <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> bashers for cutting out enough funding for the defense of this nation,'' <PERSON> Weinberger </PERSON> said on <ORGANIZATION> NBC-TV </ORGANIZATION>'s `` Meet the Press.'' The investigation of defense fraud, started by the <ORGANIZATION> Naval </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Investigative </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> nearly two years ago and now directed by the <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>, surfaced on June 14 when <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> agents served more than three dozen search warrants around the country. The warrants named some of the nation's largest defense contractors along with industry consultants and <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> workers. Among the most prominent of the consultants was <PERSON> Melvyn </PERSON> <PERSON> Paisley </PERSON>, who until April 1987 was an assistant secretary of the <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> officials say the inquiry centers on allegations that <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> executives took bribes from private military consultants who were selling classified contract information to their corporate clients. To date, the <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION>'s only official response to the investigation has been to reassign six officials of the <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> to other jobs pending the outcome of the investigation. The reassignments, including a man holding the fairly high-ranking position of deputy assistant secretary of the <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION>, are not of sufficient number to create important gaps in the procurement bureaucracy, the services said last week. `` We just do n't foresee any type of impact on the award of contracts because of these moves,'' said Lt. <PERSON> Janet </PERSON> <PERSON> Mescus </PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> spokeswoman. <PERSON> Howard </PERSON> and other officials say the scandal is simply too young to directly affect the awarding of contracts. With about 60,000 contracts being awarded every work day _ 15.3 million contracts totaling $ 156.5 billion were distributed in fiscal 1987 _ there is a momentum that is not easily arrested, they said. `` This is a massive organization,'' <PERSON> Howard </PERSON> said. `` It has 50,000 people writing contracts or involved in the contractual process.'' Another Pentagon executive agreed: `` There's no impact on awards. You ca n't stop buying F-A-18s when the <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> needs F-A-18s for its carriers. It does n't work that way.'' Industry officials counter that if they are premature with their fears, the handwriting is on the wall. Indeed, many say they are so concerned that they do n't want to talk about the scandal for fear of fanning publicity. One executive, demanding anonymity, explained: `` Here I am, staring at more competition to begin with because the defense budget is being cut; facing reduced -LRB- profit -RRB- margins because of regulatory changes, and you want me to talk about a probe that is spreading the impression the entire defense industry is crooked. No thanks.'' Underscoring the pressures being produced by the investigation, a <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> committee flirted briefly last Friday with legislation that would have allowed the government to suspend payments to defense contractors under investigation in the case. The committee decided such action would be premature, but there were predictions the matter would arise again on the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> floor.
