<HEAD>Kabul Airport Fire Destroys Eight Soviet Jet Fighters</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYAN WILDER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Western sources said Sunday that a fire at the <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION> airport in <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> destroyed eight Soviet jet fighters and may have been the result of an attack by Moslem guerrillas. The diplomatic sources, speaking on condition of anonymity, said reports coming in late Saturday said eight Soviet Su-25 jet fighters exploded one after the other at the northwest end of the airport. A telex report from one Western embassy called it `` one of the largest Soviet air losses in the war.'' The sources said their counterparts in the Afghan capital first heard of the fire Friday morning. The explosions and tracer-like eruptions indicated the fire also set off some ammunition, they said. `` It looks like a -LRB- guerrilla -RRB- attack,'' said one Western diplomat in <LOCATION> Islamabad </LOCATION>. He said reliable sources in <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION> reported seeing two incoming rockets, likely fired by insurgents, hit Theo Oga Airport about two hours after the fire was first noticed. Diplomats said the Saturday reports indicated the Soviet planes were parked almost two miles away from where the rounds hit Friday. Soviet and Afghan government forces were fighting U.S.-backed guerrillas just west of the airport, on the northern outskirts of the capital, diplomats said. The fire has shut down activities at the airport, the sources said. They said no fixed-wing aircraft have been seen landing there since the fire began, and that one Soviet Il-76 transport plane was seen being diverted on approach. However, at least one commercial flight of the Afghan airline <PERSON> Ariana </PERSON> arrived in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Delhi </LOCATION> from <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION> on Saturday, passengers said. Civil and military planes use the same runways at <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION> but it was not immediately known how many Ariana planes are using the airport. Earlier reports had described heavy military traffic at the airport as Soviets stepped up the resupply of Afghan government troops when the <ORGANIZATION> Red </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> started its nine-month withdrawal from <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> on May 15. Soviet troops intervened in <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> in December 1979 to back the <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION> government in its war with Afghan rebels. They began withdrawing under an accord signed April 14 in <LOCATION> Geneva </LOCATION>. Guerrillas claimed to have launched rocket attacks on the airport last week but not on Friday. In another development, Afghan and diplomatic sources reported rebels shot down an Afghan transport plane on June 16 near the embattled eastern garrison town of <LOCATION> Khost </LOCATION>. Diplomatic sources said Afghans put the casualty toll at 30 to 40 but were not able to confirm whether all the victims were military. The sources said the incident has reduced the number of nighttime flights into <LOCATION> Khost </LOCATION>. The flights have been the only means to resupply the garrison, which is surrounded by guerrillas near the <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION> border. Guerrillas have taken dozens of communist posts in eastern <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> since Soviet and Afghan government troops began redeploying after the <LOCATION> Geneva </LOCATION> accord. Under the agreement, the Soviets began the nine-month withdrawal on schedule on May 15. The Soviet-backed <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION> government said only Soviet troops, not Soviet military advisers, will leave.
