<TEXT>
 Police on Sunday used sticks to break up a march by women protesting a decree that made Islam the supreme law of <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION>, a witness said. The witness said that in the eastern city of <LOCATION> Lahore </LOCATION>, police confronted about 150 women demonstrating against the law, which President <PERSON> Mohammad </PERSON> <PERSON> Zia </PERSON> <PERSON> ul-Haq </PERSON> put into effect June 15 in a televised address to the nation. The witness, speaking on condition of anonymity, said police lashed out with batons. The decree makes Islam `` the supreme law of <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION>,'' but it will not affect the rights of non-Moslems or the country's business contracts with other nations, <PERSON> Zia </PERSON> said. The women said they feared the measure would negate Moslem laws introduced in 1961, which acknowledge a woman's right to divorce as well as to demand the registration of marriages and divorces. Witnesses said the protesters, who later held a sit-in, also condemned the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> for suporting `` the dictator of <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION>.'' Police arrested six of the protesters. On May 29, <PERSON> Zia </PERSON>, who is also army chief of staff, fired his entire civilian government and dissolved the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Assembly </ORGANIZATION>. He charged the elected ruling bodies with failure to implement the Islam codes. <PERSON> Zia </PERSON> hinted that elections would be announced within 90 days, but he has n't set a date. In the southern port city of <LOCATION> Karachi </LOCATION>, the head of <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION>'s opposition <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Benazir </PERSON> <PERSON> Bhutto </PERSON>, warned the president against postponing elections `` This time you -LRB- Zia -RRB- can not escape elections,'' <PERSON> Bhutto </PERSO