<FIRST>r a AM-Drought-DirtPoor Bjt   06-26 0843</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Drought-Dirt Poor, Bjt,0864</SECOND>
<HEAD>Poorest of the Poor Scorched By Drought, Too</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT DVORCHAK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP National Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TUNICA, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Farmhand <PERSON> Gus </PERSON> <PERSON> Daniels </PERSON> toils for minimum wage on a cotton and soybean farm, scraping by during the searing drought in a tin-roofed sharecropper's house that has no running water and not even an outhouse. `` It's hot enough out there to make a man quit,'' said <PERSON> Daniels </PERSON>, 41, on the fifth straight day of 100-plus-degree temperatures in the upper <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION> delta. `` You do n't want to go out in the heat. But when it's time to go to work, I'll be there,'' <PERSON> Daniels </PERSON> said Saturday. `` We survive the best we can in this county down here. Ca n't do nothing but survive.'' The worst drought in 50 years, coupled with a combination punch of record high temperatures, hits everyone in <LOCATION> Tunica </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION>, one of the poorest areas in the country. The heat always seems the hottest for those at the bottom of the bottom, but they shrug it off. `` I was raised in the hot weather,'' said <PERSON> Daniels </PERSON>, the son of a sharecropper who also was the son of a sharecropper. <PERSON> Daniels </PERSON> earns $ 3.35 an hour to work a sweat-soaked, 12-hour shift that begins at 7 a.m. daily. Although sharecropping has virtually vanished, some of the shabby shanties remain. <PERSON> Daniels </PERSON> lives with his wife and 6-year-old daughter in an unpainted wooden shack consisting of two rooms, a kitchen and a bedroom. Flattened cardboard boxes serve as wallpaper. The toilet is a bucket or a space behind a barn. Water is hauled from town a mile away. The family pays no rent but has to pay the electric bill. The house has one fan; air conditioning is a fantasy. Nothing is insulated, and the paneless windows have screens patched together with tape. On a rare day off Saturday, <PERSON> Daniels </PERSON> sharpened tools and tinkered with his truck in the front yard, which adjoins a cotton field. The farm he works, which he calls a plantation, is irrigated and has weathered the hot, dry spell so far. `` It got so dry, the boss was laying off. I guess he felt sorry for us,'' said <PERSON> Daniels </PERSON>, listening to the blues on his pickup's radio In northern <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION>, clay soil that should be as black as buckshot pellets looks white because the moisture's been baked out of it. Dust clouds rise behind tractors like smoke from a fire, then settles on long, straight rows of crops struggling to survive on lands as flat as a tabletop. At the end of a dusty dirt road in the middle of a cotton field outside of <LOCATION> Tunica </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Jerlean </PERSON> <PERSON> Simmons </PERSON> hung a load of laundry in the wilting midday sun. `` It's too hot for anything,'' said Mrs. <PERSON> Simmons </PERSON>, 35. `` Everything's drying up. I know it's affecting the farmers. I could n't even raise a garden. It burned up.'' The hum of three electric fans droned from the old sharecropper's house, consisting of three bedrooms and a kitchen topped by corrugated tin. It has no running water and no toilet. Plastic sheets make do as window panes. Mrs. <PERSON> Simmons </PERSON>' 16-year-old daughter, also named <PERSON> Jerlean </PERSON>, worked three days last week and four days the week before as a cotton chopper. The job is as unglamorous as it sounds. For 10 hours a day at the minimum wage, laborers chop weeds with hoes along cotton rows. `` It's the only kind of work we can find to do,'' said Mrs. <PERSON> Simmons </PERSON>. `` It's the only way to make a living when you ai n't got no job. Jobs is hard to find.'' About 200 hands work as choppers in <LOCATION> Tunica </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION>, where cotton is still king but the per capita wage is $ 6,800, about 30 percent lower than average in <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION>. But the dry weather even puts a crimp in that grueling endeavor. `` It's so hot and dry, the weeds are n't growing,'' said <PERSON> Owen </PERSON> <PERSON> Bibb </PERSON>, a farmer who laid off 15 choppers on Friday because he did n't need them anymore Cotton farmers kill weeds with chemicals. But unless rain falls, the chemicals do n't do their job. `` It's been so dry, chemicals do n't work very well. Choppers get the escape weeds,'' said county agent <PERSON> Dwayne </PERSON> <PERSON> Wheeler </PERSON>. `` It's not glamorous work,'' <PERSON> Wheeler </PERSON> said. `` I did it for a while. It did n't take me long to figure out I did n't want to do that the rest of my life.'' Five miles down the road from <LOCATION> Tunica </LOCATION>, at a crossroads near a granary, sits <PERSON> Clayton </PERSON>. It's the home of the <ORGANIZATION> D </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; R One-Stop, a gas station, grocery store, beer garden, pool hall and sandwich shop under a shingled roof. Sweaty men sat outside on a wooden bench in the unpaved parking lot, where an outdoor thermometer read 110 degrees in the shade. `` Everything's burning up,'' said a farmhand who identified himself as Rock, sipping an icy drink after working the fields until noon. `` It's hot as hell. If it do n't rain, there ai n't going to be nothing for nobody to do. Right now, it's rough. All we can do is look to the Lord.''
