<FIRST>r w AM-HealthResearch Bjt   06-26 0792</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Health Research, Bjt,780</SECOND>
<HEAD>Report Criticizes Research on Medicare, Medicaid Programs</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JILL LAWRENCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> is making decisions about the $ 120 billion-a-year <ORGANIZATION> Medicare </ORGANIZATION> and Medicaid programs on the basis of federal research that is often delayed or of poor quality, the <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Accounting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION> reported Sunday. The <ORGANIZATION> GAO </ORGANIZATION>, the investigative arm of <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>, said the <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Care </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Financing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> was producing reports that `` were often not fully responsive to congressional needs, were frequently late and were variable in their technical adequacy.'' The <ORGANIZATION> GAO </ORGANIZATION> attributed some of the problems to the lengthy review and revision process conducted by administration policy makers both inside and outside the health field. More than 45 million elderly, disabled and poor Americans rely on Medicare and Medicaid to pay for their health services. The <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Care </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Financing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> oversees the two programs. The financing administration also conducts research at the request of <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> or the president when cutbacks or changes are being contemplated, to determine their impact on health care. Recent studies, for example, have examined the <ORGANIZATION> Medicare </ORGANIZATION> prospective payment system for hospitals and state regulations on Medigap policies that insure people for services uncovered by <ORGANIZATION> Medicare </ORGANIZATION>. Rep. <PERSON> Ted </PERSON> <PERSON> Weiss </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-N.Y. </LOCATION>, chairman of the House Government Operations subcommittee on human resources, said the <ORGANIZATION> GAO </ORGANIZATION> report raises serious questions about how important decisions affecting health care are made. `` If policies are made on the basis of inadequate or misleading information, or if the information needed is not provided on time, then we can expect health care to deteriorate,'' <PERSON> Weiss </PERSON>, who requested the report, said in a statement. The <ORGANIZATION> GAO </ORGANIZATION> said concerns about the quality of <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Care </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Financing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> research had been expressed since 1980 by <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>, congressional agencies, the <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Human </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION>, and others. It said quality had not improved much in the last eight years. Part of the reason, the <ORGANIZATION> GAO </ORGANIZATION> said, was that <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> was mandating more and more studies while the administration was reducing the health care agency's staff and resources. The <ORGANIZATION> GAO </ORGANIZATION> studied three areas and made the following comments: _ Relevance The office said that reports to <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> suffered from a combination of vague mandates, lack of formal communications between lawmakers and researchers, and administration reviewers who deleted relevant information on the basis of policy considerations. _ Timeliness The <ORGANIZATION> GAO </ORGANIZATION> found that of 28 reports due before the summer of 1986, 26 were delivered late or were still overdue. The lateness was attributed primarily to a review-revision cycle involving officials at the health care financing agency, the <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Human </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION> and the Office of Management and Budget. Reviews `` often have lasted for months or even years,'' the agency said. _ Technical quality of research More than one-third of the projects awarded by the health care financing agency in one year were disapproved by review panels on the basis of technical inadequacy, the <ORGANIZATION> GAO </ORGANIZATION> found. This was blamed on a flawed award process and a finding that `` a technical perspective did not always dominate reviews'' by the health care financing agency, the <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Human </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION> and the Office of Management and Budget. The deputy administrator of the health care financing agency, <PERSON> Glenn </PERSON> <PERSON> Hackbarth </PERSON>, denied that his agency has been improperly influenced by policy considerations. `` Obviously, on policy issues, we do have a policy perspective that we advocate. I do n't think that's unfair,'' he said. `` I do not think there are instances where we have tried to mislead <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> by deleting relevant, factual, technical information.'' <PERSON> Hackbarth </PERSON> said that <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>, rather than the review process, is to blame for tardy reports. He said lawmakers require long lists of studies without considering the money or staff available to do them. `` It should be no surprise to anyone that there are more studies than there are resources and the end result is late reports,'' he said. <PERSON> Hackbarth </PERSON> admitted that his agency has sometimes awarded grant money to projects that are technically weak, but said it has been done when the agency had virtually no alternative. `` We can either not do any research on a pressing problem or we can decide to go ahead with a proposal that is not technically everything we would like it to be,'' he said. `` Sometimes we do the latter and I think it is entirely defensible.'' The <ORGANIZATION> GAO </ORGANIZATION> report recommended a number of steps it believes the <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Human </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION> should take, among them an assessment of whether health care financing agency has enough staff and resources to handle the reports mandated by <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> and sought by the administration. It also said the department should develop a formalized review process to ensure timely delivery of reports, and make sure there is better communication between researchers and lawmakers.
