<HEAD>League of Women Voters Starting Postcard Campaign to Get Debates</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The League of Women Voters is starting a nationwide postcard-writing campaign to try to get the 1988 presidential candidates to agree to debate under its sponsorship. Two postcards, one addressed to Republican <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> and one to Democrat <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>, are being sent to league members with an accompanying letter from <PERSON> Nancy </PERSON> <PERSON> Neuman </PERSON>, chairwoman of the group's education fund `` The shameless attempt by the two parties to ` steal' the debates threatens more than the league,'' the letter said. `` It threatens the voters.'' The postcards urge the two likely nominees to commit to the league's general election debates. The league is asking its members to mail the postcards to the two candidates. The group has sponsored presidential debates since 1976, but this year has been fighting with the Democratic and Republican parties which are holding their own debates. <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Schnur </PERSON>, a <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> spokesman, said, `` We will wait and see what the two parties decide. We are not closing any options.'' `` I know we are committed to the <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> debates,'' said <PERSON> Steve </PERSON> <PERSON> Akey </PERSON>, a <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> spokesman. `` At this point that is all we have committed to.'' Both the league and the parties are proposing three debates for the presidential candidates and one for the vice presidential candidates. The league has announced debates in <LOCATION> Birmingham </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ala. </LOCATION>; Minneapolis-St. <PERSON> Paul </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Minn. </LOCATION>; <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> The parties announced debates in <LOCATION> Annapolis </LOCATION>, Md.; <LOCATION> Winston-Salem </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.C. </LOCATION>; <LOCATION> Omaha </LOCATION>, Neb.; and <LOCATION> Pittsburgh </LOCATION>.
