<HEAD>Police Search For Clues In Singleton Home Bombing</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TAMPA, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Police were scrutinizing remnants of a crude homemade bomb tossed at the home of rapist <PERSON> Lawrence </PERSON> <PERSON> Singleton </PERSON>'s brother, but had no idea Sunday who hurled the explosive in a normally quiet <LOCATION> Tampa </LOCATION> suburb <PERSON> Walter </PERSON> <PERSON> Singleton </PERSON> and his wife, <PERSON> Dianne </PERSON>, were alone in their house when the bomb exploded Saturday night in their front yard, about 30 feet from the front door, said <LOCATION> Hillsborough </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> sheriff's spokesman <PERSON> Debbie </PERSON> <PERSON> Carter </PERSON> They were uninjured. Bomb squad experts were looking for fingerprints and other clues Sunday on bomb bits picked out of the lawn, she said. `` Our bomb squad has the fragments that are left; we think it was a homemade device,'' she said. `` We found pieces of cardboard and duct tape. We're processing them so hopefully we'll be able to tell something from that.''' There were no arrests by midday Sunday, and no one saw the bomb tossed. <PERSON> Singleton </PERSON> was convicted of raping a 15-year-old hitchhiker, chopping her arms off with an ax and leaving her for dead in a ditch southeast of <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION> in 1978. The girl survived. A 60-year-old former merchant seaman who grew up in <LOCATION> Tampa </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Lawrence </PERSON> <PERSON> Singleton </PERSON> spent eight years of a 14-year sentence in a <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> prison. He completed a year-long probation and is now free to live where he pleases. During his probation, he was forced to live in a trailer on the grounds of <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Quentin </LOCATION> prison grounds because of bitter protest in several communities that were proposed as homes for him. The blast left an impression about four feet across in the yard, but no damage to the house that <PERSON> Singleton </PERSON> listed with state officials as his <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> address, said sheriff's Maj. <PERSON> Ron </PERSON> <PERSON> Poindexter </PERSON>. `` At first we thought it was a lightning bolt, then we looked out of our window and saw smoke,'' said neighbor <PERSON> Harrie </PERSON> <PERSON> Grimes </PERSON>. Neighbors happened to see a red vehicle in the area, but authorities do n't know if it was the same one from which the bomb was hurled, Ms. <PERSON> Carter </PERSON> said. Since <PERSON> Lawrence </PERSON> <PERSON> Singleton </PERSON> registered his brother's address with the state, neighbors have been frightened and upset. A local businessman and a radio station have each offered <PERSON> Singleton </PERSON> $ 5,000 if he will pack up and go anywhere else. <PERSON> Walter </PERSON> <PERSON> Singleton </PERSON> says his brother lives `` about two hours away'' from here, but refuses to say exactly where. Ms. <PERSON> Carter </PERSON> said it was unclear if the bombing would further upset residents of the <LOCATION> Forest </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hills </LOCATION> neighborhood. `` It's too early to tell if this is going to add fuel to the fire, so to speak,'' she said. `` We have patrols in the area that make periodic checks on Mr. <PERSON> Singleton </PERSON>'s home.''
