<FIRST>r a AM-EmbattledEditor Bjt   06-26 0797</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Embattled Editor, Bjt,0822</SECOND>
<HEAD>Politicians Bring Rare Criminal Libel Charges Against Newspaper
Editor</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TRIP DuBARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KINGSTREE, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Two years ago, an editor besieged by <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Fitts </PERSON>' letters to his newspaper suggested that the retired agriculture teacher start up his own publication to voice his opinions. <PERSON> Fitts </PERSON> took the advice, and today his fledgling weekly is in the midst of a legal battle involving First Amendment rights. <PERSON> Fitts </PERSON>, the 62-year-old editor of <LOCATION> Williamsburg </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION>'s The <ORGANIZATION> Voice </ORGANIZATION> newspaper, not only stirred up the political powers that be in this poor, rural county of some 40,000 people. His denunciation of two politicians and subsequent arrest on criminal libel charges caught the attention of journalists around the country. <PERSON> Fitts </PERSON> has gone to jail once and could go again for expressing his opinion in a newspaper. He awaits word Monday on whether he has been indicted by a <LOCATION> Williamsburg </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> grand jury on criminal libel charges. If indicted and convicted, he faces a fine of up to $ 5,000 and a year in jail. `` Clearly, we've got a political commentator making a political statement about two politicians,'' said <PERSON> Jane </PERSON> <PERSON> Kirtley </PERSON>, executive director of the <ORGANIZATION> Reporters </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Freedom </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> the </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>. `` It seems to me that punishing someone for speaking is not an American concept.'' But <PERSON> Fitts </PERSON>' targets see something more in the caustic column he wrote before the June 14 primary elections. State Rep. <PERSON> B.J </PERSON>. <PERSON> Gordon </PERSON> and state Sen. <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> McGill </PERSON> say <PERSON> Fitts </PERSON>' attacks, in which he accuses them of stealing and corruption without offering evidence, are lying, hurtful shots that deserve to be punished `` Freedom of the press is not to go around with freedom and accuse people of committing crimes,'' <PERSON> Gordon </PERSON> said. The two politicians have brought what is believed to be only the fourth criminal libel suit in <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Carolina </LOCATION> in 40 years, and the first in the nation since 1984. Although civil libel cases are not unusual and often result in the awarding of monetary damages to the aggrieved party, criminal libel cases are rare because they can send a journalist to jail. <PERSON> Fitts </PERSON>, who spent 13 years as an agriculture teacher in <PERSON> Dillon </PERSON> and <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Myrtle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Beach </LOCATION> and 20 years as <ORGANIZATION> Clemson </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>'s agricultural extension agent in <LOCATION> Williamsburg </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION>, retired in 1986 and began sending letters to the county's only newspaper over a controversial school board issue After a while, he said, the editor suggested <PERSON> Fitts </PERSON> needed his own paper to publish his opinions. `` I said, ` That's a good idea; I had n't thought about that,''' he recalled in an interview Thursday. Roughly six months later, in January 1987, a new weekly began rolling off the presses, and from the beginning it expressed <PERSON> Fitts </PERSON>' outspoken style `` I've always been opinionated,'' he said. `` I just have an opinion and I have no problem sharing it.'' He may have a problem sharing it for a while, however. The judge who set his bond also put him under a gag order forbidding him to discuss his arrest. He spent a weekend in jail under $ 40,000 bond before he was released on his own recognizance. <PERSON> Gordon </PERSON> and <ORGANIZATION> McGill </ORGANIZATION> think <PERSON> Fitts </PERSON> crossed the line with a May 17 column, in which he wrote: `` I will say to you, without fear of contradiction, if every black in <LOCATION> Williamsburg </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> would start stealing today and steal every day for the rest of their lives, they could not steal as much as those two have stolen during their time in power.'' The column gave no specifics, and when asked what he thought they had stolen, he said only that they had taken the pride of people of <LOCATION> Williamsburg </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION>. He stressed that he was not apologizing for what he wrote but acknowledged that he could have chosen his words better. `` I'm not trained as a journalist. I do n't know how to polish things,'' he said. `` Maybe if I had polished it, I could have gotten it across better.'' <PERSON> Fitts </PERSON>, who is black, has said that the dispute with the two politicians is economic, not racial. <PERSON> Gordon </PERSON> is black and <ORGANIZATION> McGill </ORGANIZATION> is white. The Voice, with a circulation of 2,300, has a largely black readership. Despite what people like <PERSON> Kirtley </PERSON> say, <PERSON> Gordon </PERSON> and <ORGANIZATION> McGill </ORGANIZATION>'s lawyer said the criminal libel law is still a good one. `` I do n't think the press has been fair in the matter,'' said attorney <PERSON> Wallace </PERSON> <PERSON> Connor </PERSON>. `` I can understand ... they want to protect themselves. `` There is a statute in this state against libel and slander. They -LRB- the media -RRB- say that it's antiquated, but as long as it's a law, it ought to be obeyed,'' <PERSON> Connor </PERSON> said. `` Also, if it's antiquated, the Ten Commandments are antiquated, because they were written 5,000 years ago and it says ` Thou shalt not bear false witness,''' he said.
