<HEAD>Boy Scouts Help Drought-Stricken Willits To Lay Emergency Pipeline</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Drought-Dirt Poor Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto SC1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEVE GEISSINGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WILLITS, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The Boy Scouts have rescued this isolated city from the possibility that it would run out of drinking water by the end of a drought-baked summer. A 2-mile-long, 8-inch pipeline, planned to be finished in a few weeks, will link a Boy Scout camp reservoir with an undersized, rundown municipal water system. The Scouts are letting the town have the water for free. `` It gets a little thirsty around here when it does n't rain,'' <PERSON> Alan </PERSON> <PERSON> Birket </PERSON>, city water supervisor, said last week. The Scout organization agreed to help last October after the town of about 5,000 in a coastal valley 120 miles north of <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION> declared a state of emergency. Officials expected the city's reservoir to run out by Thanksgiving. A convoy of trucks from a variety of government agencies hauled in pipe loaned by the state. Forklifts from private companies unloaded it. Workers from the state conservation youth corps began clamping it together. All was at no cost to the ranching community in <LOCATION> Mendocino </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION>. Then the rains came, so the pipeline was left unfinished. However, only two-thirds of the normal 50 inches fell, not enough to ward off fears that the city could run dry this summer. Now the city plans to finish the pipeline and begin pumping water before its reservoir is drawn too far down. But some folks think the pipeline should already have been completed in <LOCATION> Willits </LOCATION>, the only <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> city that's declared a state of emergency because of the drought. `` People are always talking about it. It's not even finished. It's just sitting out there,'' said <PERSON> Kelli </PERSON> <PERSON> Fuller </PERSON>, a 30-year-old waitress at Mom's Place on Main Street, which is also <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> 101. People are n't really worried, though, she added, plunking down glasses of water for two customers who had n't asked for them, in violation of voluntary city conservation rules. She explained, with a shrug, `` It's hot today.'' Water conservation will shift from voluntary to mandatory Friday, city Manager <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Van </PERSON> <PERSON> Orden </PERSON> said. People who wash cars or hose driveways can be fined $ 500. Sprinklers also will be shut off at some city parks. `` If you waste water, you have neighbors telling on you,'' he said. Voluntary measures, <PERSON> Van </PERSON> <PERSON> Orden </PERSON> said, have cut average daily water usage significantly because `` the city officials asking for cutbacks are residents' next-door neighbors, not people they do n't know _ like in larger cities. `` We're all running around with dirty cars and not watering our yards in the daytime,'' said <PERSON> Elin </PERSON> <PERSON> Crawford </PERSON>, an adult education teacher. The drought has worsened water problems Willits already faced, but the city is working to ensure that the headaches do n't persist. The city has secured $ 3.3 million in state loans to improve its water system and expand its reservoir.
