<HEAD>Refusenik Protest Lasts 20 Minutes Before Leader Is Detained</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN-THOR DAHLBURG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Soviet Jews demanding the right to emigrate gathered on a <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> street Sunday, but within minutes their posters were ripped down and police took away the group's leader. <PERSON> Yuri </PERSON> <PERSON> Semenovsky </PERSON> and about 10 other Soviet Jews came to the Arbat, a bustling pedestrian mall in central <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>, to protest legislation they say prevents them from leaving the country. Soviet officials say the only bar to emigration is knowledge of state secrets, but <PERSON> Semenovsky </PERSON> and the others said they can not leave because of a law requiring documentation that they do n't owe money to relatives or ex-spouses. A law passed in August 1986 requires that the documentation be provided by would-be emigrants' relatives. <PERSON> Semenovsky </PERSON> said Soviet citizens have no legal way to make a relative provide such information. `` The courts are no help,'' said the former mathematician, who lost his job when he applied to leave the country more than two years ago. `` They have been told not to get involved in cases involving refuseniks. More than 200,000 Soviet Jews want to leave, but ca n't.'' At 4 p.m., <PERSON> Semenovsky </PERSON> and the others, members of a refusenik group called the Poor Relatives, assembled in front of a building on the Arbat. They taped four small posters on the wooden fence that surrounds the building. One read: `` If you want to know the truth about refuseniks, and not the usual lies and filth from the newspapers and <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Television </ORGANIZATION>, read the informational leaflet from the ` Poor Relatives' Group.'' Scores of Soviets assembled to scan the posters. Ten minutes after the posters went up, two men dressed in civilian clothes ripped them down, walked away and threw them into the trash. A water truck usually used to hose down Soviet streets passed close to the group clustered around the posters, forcing them closer to the wooden fence. `` It's the <ORGANIZATION> KGB </ORGANIZATION>,'' said <PERSON> Semenovsky </PERSON>. A police lieutenant came up to <PERSON> Semenovsky </PERSON> and asked him to accompany him to a district court. <PERSON> Semenovsky </PERSON> asked if he was being detained. `` I invite you to accompany me because of administrative violations you have committed,'' the policeman said. `` What violations?'' <PERSON> Semenovsky </PERSON> asked. `` You know very well,'' the lieutenant said. <PERSON> Semenovsky </PERSON> refused to go, and the lieutenant left. A few minutes later, four uniformed police officers picked their way through the scores of people who had gathered around the demonstrators and grabbed <PERSON> Semenovsky </PERSON>. The policemen held the refusenik tightly under the arms as they took him to a small green sedan. He was then driven away. Jewish emigration last month from the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> reached 1,145, its highest monthly total in seven years, but <PERSON> Jewish </PERSON> activists say tens of thousands of Soviet Jews have had their applications for an exit visa rejected. <PERSON> Semenovsky </PERSON> has said he can not get an affadavit from his former wife, <PERSON> Galina </PERSON>, that attests he does not owe her any money. He said he tried three times to get <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> courts to force her to give him the document but that the courts refused. On Saturday, about 200 people refused to allow police to break up a demonstration on <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>'s <LOCATION> Pushkin </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Square </LOCATION> by the <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION>, a recently created group that wants to challenge the political monopoly of the <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>. At least three people were detained by police at that protest. Also Saturday, 1975 Nobel Peace Prize winner and diss