<HEAD>YWCA Votes To Continue To Bar Men, Despite Legal Threat</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Pene is cq in 16th graf</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By LINDSEY TANNER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The national <ORGANIZATION> YWCA </ORGANIZATION>, facing a court battle over a <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> state chapter's decision to hire a man as a leader, has voted to retain the all-female status it has held for 130 years, its national president said Sunday. But the organization's board of directors postponed a vote on whether to expel the <LOCATION> Tacoma </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Wash. </LOCATION>, chapter for hiring a man as executive director, said President <PERSON> Glendora </PERSON> <PERSON> McIlwain </PERSON> <PERSON> Putnam </PERSON>. The chapter has sued to remain a part of the national organization, which concluded its 31st national convention Sunday at a downtown hotel. At the five-day meeting, an estimated 1,200 delegates from local chapters across the country voted overwhelmingly to continue to exclude men as full voting members, Ms. <PERSON> Putnam </PERSON> said. `` It is now more important than ever that the <ORGANIZATION> YWCA </ORGANIZATION> remain an autonomous women's membership movement because of the serious challenges which confront women in the areas of employment, housing, child-care and poverty,'' she said. `` The <ORGANIZATION> YWCA </ORGANIZATION>'s position is an affirmative response to inequity and disparity which continue to be the rule rather than the exception,'' she said. The Young Women's <ORGANIZATION> Christian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> was founded in 1858 as an organization exclusively for women, partly to address the problems of housing, poverty-level wages and educational opportunities for young women who flocked to cities during the Industrial Revolution. `` The fundamental focus of our organization has been the same ... the empowerment of women and girls ... making them more in control of their lives,'' Ms. <PERSON> Putnam </PERSON> said. Under the group's constitution, men can participate as associates, but not as full, voting members. The constitution also says that executive directors should be full, voting members, said spokeswoman <PERSON> Claire </PERSON> <PERSON> Carroll </PERSON>. Earlier this year, the <PERSON> Odgen </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Utah </LOCATION>, chapter became the first in the country to lose its affiliation for allowing men to join as full members. The chapter still has time to reconsider its action before it is barred from using the <ORGANIZATION> YWCA </ORGANIZATION> name and logo, Ms. <PERSON> Putnam </PERSON> said. Although recent court decisions have forced several formerly all-male groups such as the <ORGANIZATION> Jaycees </ORGANIZATION> to admit women, Ms. <PERSON> Putnam </PERSON> said she does not consider the YWCA policy discriminatory. Those earlier court rulings have been aimed at allowing women into places `` where business is discussed,'' she said. `` We're not a marketplace issue. We do n't come to the <ORGANIZATION> YWCA </ORGANIZATION> to discuss business,'' Ms. <PERSON> Putnam </PERSON> said. Rather, the <ORGANIZATION> YWCA </ORGANIZATION> offers services aimed solely at women, such as child-care, programs for battered women and fitness classes, she said. `` Women need a place where they can be comfortable expressing their problems, their fears, the way they face the world. They need to discuss it with other women,'' she said. <PERSON> Pene </PERSON> <PERSON> Modahl </PERSON>, president of the <LOCATION> Tacoma </LOCATION> chapter's board of directors, has said that hiring <PERSON> Alan </PERSON> <PERSON> Tiger </PERSON> as executive director will not hurt that goal. She called him `` the best possible candidate, who happened to be a man.'' The <LOCATION> Tacoma </LOCATION> chapter filed suit June 10 in <LOCATION> Pierce </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Wash. </LOCATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Superior </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> seeking to bar the national board from expelling it. Ms. <PERSON> Put