<HEAD>Bush Points Finger At Congress In Anti-Drug Speech</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RITA BEAMISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLUMBUS, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Vice President <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> on Sunday accused <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> of inaction in the fight against drugs, but a representative of Democrat <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> immediately turned the blame on the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration. In speeches at a conference of the <ORGANIZATION> Fraternal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Order </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Police </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> and <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> supporter Sen. <PERSON> Dennis </PERSON> <PERSON> DeConcini </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Ariz </LOCATION>., each laid the blame for failing to quell the drug crisis at the other's <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, the certain Republican presidential nominee, also said he would be tough in prosecution of drug dealers and would convert unneeded military bases into minimum security prisons. He said he had no specific bases in mind but would expect his secretary of defense to review the matter. On the drug issue, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said, `` <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> is full of rhetorical heroes on the issue of drugs, but when it comes to law enforcement, some of them go AWOL,'' short for absent without leave. He said <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> reduced the administration's <ORGANIZATION> Coast </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION> budget request last year by $ 72 million, and by $ 864 million over four years. But <PERSON> DeConcini </PERSON> claimed it was the administration that did the cutting and <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> that restored dollars for drug-fighting efforts. He said the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration's 1988 budget sought a $ 900 million cut in anti-drug funds, including money for <ORGANIZATION> Coast </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Border </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Patrol </ORGANIZATION> interdiction efforts. It also included a 60 percent cut in drug prevention and education programs. <PERSON> DeConcini </PERSON> said <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> restored 70 percent of the funds and he labeled <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s claim of congressional laxity as `` just a bogus argument.'' In a prepared statement, <PERSON> DeConcini </PERSON> also accused <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> of personal failure as head of the National Narcotics Border Interdiction System. <PERSON> DeConcini </PERSON> said the panel `` was found to be an organization of half-empty offices lacking organization'' and added that it virtually ignored the air charters that are `` the most commmon means of smuggling cocaine into southern <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION>.'' <PERSON> DeConcini </PERSON> said he was addressing the group as a surrogate for <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>, who has sewn up the Democratic presidential nomination and is spending a few days vacationing in <LOCATION> Nantucket </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mass </LOCATION>. In a news conference after his speech, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> debunked a report that his aides have zeroed in on Sen. <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Dole </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Kansas </LOCATION> as the leading candidate to become <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s running mate. `` Nobody is authorized to peak in my behalf,'' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said of the report in Sunday's <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION>. `` We have not begun the process in terms of lists,'' he said. `` There is n't a long list or a short list.'' <PERSON> Dole </PERSON>, while campaigning for <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> on Saturday in <LOCATION> Oregon </LOCATION>, was asked about chances he would be the running mate and said: `` If I got the call, I'd say, ` Mr. Vice President, let's talk,' but that has n't happened.'' Discussing what he will look for in a running mate, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said, `` I want to have an inclusion of the vice president on things. That suggests a certain philosophical compatibility, not on every single issue, but a philosophical compatibility and a tempermental compatibility ... so you're not looking over wondering if the vice president is posturing and cutting up the president.'' In his remarks to the police group, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> called for: mandatory testing of `` anyone responsible for the public safety,'' recriminalization of drug possession in states where it has been decriminalized, the death penalty for drug kingpins and those who commit drug-related murders, and continuation of the `` zero tolerance'' policy aimed at users of drugs in even small amounts.
