<HEAD>UN Disarmament Session Ends Without Final Document</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER JAMES SPIELMANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A special <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Assembly </ORGANIZATION> session on disarmament ended in failure Sunday after delegates failed to adopt a final document on nuclear arms reduction. The session ended Sunday morning after committee meetings could not end differences in disarmament positions held by the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> and developing nations and a more cautious approach backed by the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and some of its Western allies. The four-week session of the 159-member <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Assembly </ORGANIZATION>, the third in 10 years to focus on disarmament, cost the financially ailing <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> about $ 7.4 million. Delegates never voted on a final document. Committee delegates decided not to attempt to pass a resolution without consensus. The <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Assembly </ORGANIZATION> has no enforcement power over its decisions. Delegates believed a final resolution adopted by consensus, however, would carry the moral authority of expressing the will of the world community. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and some of its Western allies opposed most other nations on issues ranging from the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> space-based defense program known as `` Star Wars,'' the monitoring of land-based weapons, and a Soviet call for a joint U.S.-Soviet nuclear test ban. <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> officials described the past week's committee debates as `` very intense and arduous.'' Some delegates said there were sharp confrontations and shouting in at least one closed session. `` A certain country which should have important disarmament responsibilities had insisted on its position. That was a major reason that consensus was not achieved,'' said <LOCATION> Chinese </LOCATION> delegate <PERSON> Yu </PERSON> <PERSON> Mengyia </PERSON>, referring to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> delegate <PERSON> Vladimir </PERSON> <PERSON> F. </PERSON> <PERSON> Petrovsky </PERSON> also noted that no agreement was possible `` because of the actions of some states.'' <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> delegate <PERSON> Max </PERSON> <PERSON> Friedersdorf </PERSON> said the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> `` regretted very much that it had not been possible to achieve consensus on the chairman's draft document, which had been acceptable in large part to most delegations.'' During the special session, the Soviets called for the elimination of all nuclear weapons by the end of the century; troop reductions of 500,000 soldiers each by the <ORGANIZATION> Warsaw </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pact </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> and a ban on `` Star Wars.'' Since the session began May 31, the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> was also at odds with other positions favored by the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>, including an expanded role for the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> in multilateral verification of nuclear weapons and naval nuclear disarmament. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> favored emphasis on conventional disarmament, especially in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>, where the <LOCATION> Warsaw </LOCATION> Pact is regarded as having military superiority.
