<HEAD>Former Candidate Shirley Chisholm Says Gender Gap Could Disappear</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DARREN DOPP</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BUFFALO, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The `` gender gap'' giving Democrat <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> an early lead over Republican <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> might disappear on Election Day, said former presidential candidate <PERSON> Shirley </PERSON> <PERSON> Chisholm </PERSON> who warned that factors dividing female voters should not be underestimated. Even though most women prefer <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>, the likely <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> nominee, it does n't mean they will vote for him in November, <PERSON> Chisholm </PERSON> told about 1,000 delegates to the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Women </ORGANIZATION> conference in <LOCATION> Buffalo </LOCATION>. `` We're not as monolithic as led to believe,'' she said, noting regional, economic and age difference among women voters. `` You constantly talk about being 53 percent of the vote, but if you are unable to deliver that, you will be ignored,'' said the former <LOCATION> Brooklyn </LOCATION> congresswoman who ran for president in 1972. <PERSON> Chisholm </PERSON> said there was similar talk of a gender gap in 1984 when the Republican ticket of <PERSON> Ronald </PERSON> <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> and <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> handed the Democratic ticket of <PERSON> Walter </PERSON> <PERSON> Mondale </PERSON> and <PERSON> Geraldine </PERSON> <PERSON> Ferrao </PERSON> a disastrous defeat. `` Many women, particulary southern women, could n't identify with <PERSON> Ferraro </PERSON>,'' she said. `` We've got ask why and learn from our mistakes.'' Part of the problem, she said, is that feminists are often intolerant of opposing views. For the last decade, she said, women's right groups have judged candidates mainly on their abortion postions. Women candidate who are not pro-choice are often opposed, she said. `` You ca n't use one issue as a litmus test,'' she said. `` You ca n't be that emotional about politics.'' She said Democratic women should recognize that the party will need to have a southerner or someone acceptable to southerners on the ticket if it expects to win in November. `` You had better be prepared to accomodate the more conservative views of southern women if you expect to maintain national political power,'' she said. `` You ca n't afford to alienate them.'' <PERSON> Chisholm </PERSON> campaigned for <PERSON> Jesse </PERSON> <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> this year.
