<BYLINE>By DARREN DOPP</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NIAGARA FALLS, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A teen-ager beat his mother to death the morning he was to graduate as valedictorian of his class, apparently because she was being overbearingly protective, police said Sunday. `` He claimed his mother would n't give him any freedom,'' Detective Lt. <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Clute </PERSON> said. <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Shrubsall </PERSON>, 17, was in jail without bond Sunday after police said he confessed to using a baseball bat to crush the skull of his 56-year-old mother, <PERSON> Marianne </PERSON>, during an argument about 3 a.m. Saturday. The boy said his mother hit him first, <PERSON> Clute </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Shrubsall </PERSON>, who is scheduled to be arraigned Monday, was charged with murder just 10 hours before he was to graduate with honors from <ORGANIZATION> LaSalle </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> High </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION>. The graduation ceremony was held as scheduled Saturday, but with no valedictory speech and no mention of the killing, said principal <PERSON> Ralph </PERSON> <PERSON> Guerrucci </PERSON>. <PERSON> Guerrucci </PERSON> said school officials did not want to remind the class of 250 students of the tragedy, `` but it definitely dampened the day.'' `` The graduates were understandaly upset. ... Obviously, they do n't want the day to be remembered by what happened to their valedictorian,'' the principal said. Friends and neighbors reacted with disbelief that the crime could have been committed by the handsome and popular teen-ager, who hoped to become a lawyer and was to attend the highly selective <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> in the fall. `` You ca n't say anything bad about him. ... He was just supernice,'' said <PERSON> Darlene </PERSON> <PERSON> Irish </PERSON>, a neighbor whose father had called police. `` And his mom was one of those, ` Can I do anything for you?' persons. ... She was alwa