<HEAD>Tatar Protest Brutally Dispersed By Police</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 5 grafs to UPDATE with protester's report from
Tashkent. Picks up 3rd graf previous, ``The demonstration ...</NOTE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Club-wielding police brutally dispersed thousands of Crimean Tatars who massed Sunday to protest the <LOCATION> Kremlin </LOCATION>'s refusal to give them back their homeland, a protester said Sunday <PERSON> Server </PERSON> <PERSON> Tuvarchy </PERSON>, who took part in the demonstration in the <LOCATION> Uzbekistan </LOCATION> capital of <LOCATION> Tashkent </LOCATION>, said 5,000 people gathered on the city's Revolution Square in front of Communist party headquarters. `` The militia beat people,'' <PERSON> Tuvarchy </PERSON>, a Crimean Tatar activist, said in a telephone interview. `` I myself took a girl to the hospital who had been beaten so badly she was unconscious.'' <PERSON> Tuvarchy </PERSON> said at least two people had been arrested. He said at <LOCATION> Tashkent </LOCATION>'s southern railway station, up to 300 Tatars had been held by police to prevent them from taking part in the protest. In <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>, dissident <PERSON> Valery </PERSON> <PERSON> Senderov </PERSON> quoted telephone reports from <LOCATION> Tashkent </LOCATION> as saying up to 20,000 people took part in the demonstration in front of Communist Party headquarters. `` The demonstration was roughly broken up by militiamen who kicked the participants and beat them with clubs,'' <PERSON> Senderov </PERSON> said in a telephone interview. He said reports telephoned from the scene said hundreds may have been injured. The demonstration in <LOCATION> Tashkent </LOCATION>, about 1,600 miles southeast of <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>, was called to protest a government decision this month that denied the Crimean Tatars their own homeland, <PERSON> Senderov </PERSON> said. On June 9, a government commission led by President <PERSON> Andrei </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gromyko </PERSON> ruled that there were `` no grounds for establishing a <LOCATION> Crimean </LOCATION> autonomy.'' That announcement was a major setback for the Tatars, who for decades have been demanding a return to their ancestral homeland on the <LOCATION> Black </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Sea </LOCATION>. Dictator <PERSON> Josef </PERSON> <PERSON> V. </PERSON> <PERSON> Stalin </PERSON> deported the Tatars from the <LOCATION> Crimea </LOCATION> during World War II for allegedly collaborating with the <ORGANIZATION> Nazis </ORGANIZATION>. The Crimean Tatars, who today number from 250,000 to 300,000, were absolved of the war collaboration charge in 1967 but were still not allowed to return en masse to the <LOCATION> Crimea </LOCATION>. A statement issued by the government commission said the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> had eased restrictions that barred some Tatars from returning to the <LOCATION> Crimea </LOCATION>. `` Since the middle of 1987, some 2,500 Crimean Tatars have been granted residence permits and fixed up with jobs in the <LOCATION> Crimea </LOCATION>,'' the commission said. Crimean Tatar leaders have said those measures are inadequate, and they have demanded the revival of the Crimean Tatar autonomous region abolished by <PERSON> Stalin </PERSON>. <PERSON> Senderov </PERSON> said the demonstrators in <LOCATION> Tashkent </LOCATION> were also protesting the treatment of Crimean Tatars in <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>. Authorities in the Soviet capital, bent on preventing Tatar demonstrations during the nationwide <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> conference that begins Tuesday, are immediately sending Crimean Tatars who arrive in <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> back home, <PERSON> Senderov </PERSON> said. One activist drew a 10-day jail term for arguing with a <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> police officer, he said. <PERSON> Senderov </PERSON> said the protesters in <LOCATION> Tashkent </LOCATION> managed to deliver a petition listing their grievances to someone at <LOCATION> Uzbekistan </LOCATION>'s Communist Party headquarters before the protest was broken up The government commission on the Crimean Tatars was established last summer, after members of the ethnic group held an extraordinary overnight demonstration at Red Square to press their demands.
