<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A group that helped defeat a referendum to finance a rail and subway system in <LOCATION> Dallas </LOCATION> and its suburbs recommended Sunday that a streamlined transit authority find other ways to ease traffic congestion. Some 59 percent of the voters in <LOCATION> Dallas </LOCATION> and 15 suburbs, the area served by <ORGANIZATION> Dallas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Area </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rapid </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Transit </ORGANIZATION>, rejected a proposal Saturday to sell $ 1 billion in bonds to begin construction of a 93-mile commuter rail system. The outcome was a victory for a group called <ORGANIZATION> Sensible </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Metro </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Area </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rapid </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Transit </ORGANIZATION>, which waged a small-budget campaign against the bond proposal. `` I think <PERSON> DART </PERSON> is at a crossroads,'' former <LOCATION> Dallas </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> Judge <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Fox </PERSON>, a leader of the citizens' group, said Sunday. `` The election is now behind us. We now have the opportunity to reassess where we are, what we've learned, and decide how to proceed from here.'' Saturday's results represented a turnabout from 1982, when 58 percent of the voters approved the measure that established DART, a regional agency that was to develop a mass transit plan, including a regional rail system. The decision throws the transit agency's future into question because suburbs may call an election to withdraw from the agency. <LOCATION> Dallas </LOCATION> suburbs contribute about 45 percent of its financing. The agency had no official contingency plan in the event of a defeat and `` will return to the drawing board,'' said <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Anderson </PERSON>, its executive director. Some transit authority board members see the bond vote as a mandate to develop a new transportation plan. Virt