<BYLINE>By TEDDIE WEYR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SALZBURG, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Pope <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> II </PERSON> on Sunday condemned the Nazi killings of thousands of severely handicapped people as `` the worst forms of barbarism'' and warned of mankind's potential for violence and destruction. `` Human life should not be divided into that which is worth living and that which is not,'' <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> told 1,000 elderly, sick and handicapped people in <LOCATION> Salzburg </LOCATION>'s cathedral. In the German Third Reich, the <ORGANIZATION> Nazis </ORGANIZATION> killed thousands of the handicapped under what they called `` euthanasia programs'' or mercy killings. `` Decades ago, this division led to the worst forms of barbarism,'' said the pontiff on the fourth day of his five-day visit to <LOCATION> Austria </LOCATION>. The 50th anniversary of <LOCATION> Austria </LOCATION>'s annexation by <ORGANIZATION> Nazi </ORGANIZATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> has prompted widespread soul-searching in this Alpine nation. Jewish leaders have called on him to urge Austrians to come to terms with the country's Nazi-era past. The pontiff often has called for greater respect for the handicapped and for elderly people who are sick. The <LOCATION> Vatican </LOCATION> is vehemently opposed to mercy killing, saying it goes against <PERSON> Christ </PERSON>'s teachings. After the prayer service, the pontiff donned a green robe and warned of drug abuse in an outdoor Mass before 25,000 people in <LOCATION> Salzburg </LOCATION>'s Residence Square. In his homily, <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> cited `` the fear of man's dangerous potential for violence and destruction'' and urged parents to `` help your adolescent sons and daughters to withstand the temptations of escaping into the sham world of drugs.'' Also Sunday, in a gesture of reconciliation, the pontiff took part in an ecumenical prayer service in a Lutheran church with representatives of 12 other <ORGANIZATION> Ch