<DATELINE>ROME (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Pope <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> II </PERSON> plans to announce an overhaul of the <LOCATION> Vatican </LOCATION> government aimed at streamlining the organization, Italian newspapers reported Sunday. The reorganization is to be announced Tuesday, the day the pontiff is scheduled to formally install 25 cardinals. The reforms will increase the <ORGANIZATION> Roman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION>'s control over the <LOCATION> Vatican </LOCATION> bank, give the Secretariat of State more power and establish a commission for relations between the <LOCATION> Vatican </LOCATION> and its lay employees, the newspapers said. The church hierarchy has been discussing the reform of the <LOCATION> Vatican </LOCATION> government, known as the Curia, for several years. The Milan-based newspaper <ORGANIZATION> Corriere </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> della </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sera </ORGANIZATION> reported the plan would give the <ORGANIZATION> College </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cardinals </ORGANIZATION> responsibility for supervising the <LOCATION> Vatican </LOCATION> bank, officially called the <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Religious </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Works </ORGANIZATION>, which has traditionally answered only to the pope. The bank has been the subject of controversy since Italian authorities issued arrest warrants in February 1987 for its president, American Archbishop <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Marcinkus </PERSON>, and two of its lay employees in connection with <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION>'s largest banking scandal. Prosecutors accused the men of being accessories to the fraudulent bankruptcy of the <ORGANIZATION> Banco </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ambrosiano </ORGANIZATION> in 1982. <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Constitutional </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> ruled earlier in July that Italian courts could not prosecute the three because the <LOCATION> Vatican </LOCATION> was considered a sovereign state under treaties between <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> Vatican </LOCATION>. According to the newspaper reports, the reform will trim the influence of the <LOCATION> Vatican </LOCATION>'s `` <ORGANIZATION> Foreign </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION>'' _ the <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> the </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Public </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Affairs </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> the </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION> _ making it just another department of the Secretariat of State. The Council has functioned as part of the Secretariat but has enjoyed a high profile and a certain amount of autonomy. The last major reform of the Curia was announced in 1967 by Pope <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> VI </PERSON>. It provided that modern languages could be used in official documents, made diocesan bishops members of all <LOCATION> Vatican </LOCATION> government departments and implemented changes brought about by the <ORGANIZATION> Second </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Vatican </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION>, which ran from 1962-65.
