<HEAD>Heart Association Approves Plan to OK Some Foods</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ST. LOUIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The American <ORGANIZATION> Heart </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> approved a system Sunday to identify and endorse processed foods that meet the group's dietary guidelines. The association said it will look mainly at the salt, cholesterol and fat levels in food products in deciding whether to endorse them as `` heart-healthy.'' Items bearing the group's seal of approval are expected to reach shelves within a year. `` We regard this new initiative as a logical expansion of the American <ORGANIZATION> Heart </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>'s well-established role as the public's chief advocate, and efforts to reduce premature death and disability from heart disease and stroke,'' said Dr. <PERSON> W.W. </PERSON> <PERSON> Aston </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Dallas </LOCATION>, chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> AHA </ORGANIZATION> task force that studied the product approval idea for the past two years The first group of foods that will be examined by an independent testing group will be margarines, cooking oils and salad dressings. The association does not expect to endorse meats, fruits and other non-processed food items. The recommendation was made at the annual delegate assembly in <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Louis </LOCATION>, which began Friday and ended Sunday. There were about 140 affiliates and scientific counsels represented at the delegate assembly. The delegates are the policy-making group for the AHA. Heart and blood vessel diseases are the nation's leading killers, and took nearly 1 million lives in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> in 1985, the most recent year for which statistics are complete. The AHA said nearly 65 million Americans have one or more forms of the diseases. Members of the task force said Sunday that dietary control is one of the most effective ways to reduce the risk of cardiovascular disease. Since 1961, the <ORGANIZATION> AHA </ORGANIZATION> has been recommending a diet low in fat, salt and cholesterol as a way to help reduce heart disease. `` Many Americans have adopted healthier eating habits, and dietary improvements recommended by the AHA clearly have played a part in the welcome decline in heart attack and stroke death rates that we have seen in the last two decades,'' <PERSON> Aston </PERSON> said. He added that two independent nationwide surveys of consumers and health specialists showed that they responded favorably to the AHA's efforts, and wanted more specific information about fat and cholesterol levels. The program will include creation of a consumer health information program. It will establish a toll-free national nutritional telephone hotline that will be staffed by registered dietitians who will give information about nutrition and risk factors for heart disease to the public and health professionals. The program also will include media campaigns and a brochure listing products that receive the AHA stamp of approval. The brochures will describe the program and provide other facts about risk factors, with an emphasis on the dangers of cigarette smoking and high blood pressure.
