<HEAD>AMA's Proposal To Create New Class of Health Worker Draws Nurses'
Fire</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Adds 4 final grafs with opening speech, administrator's
recommendation about animal research.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM C. HIDLAY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Nurses are squaring off with the nation's largest group of doctors for a battle this week over a physicians' proposal to offset the nursing shortage by creating a new class of bedside hospital worker. Doctors attending the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>'s annual policymaking convention, which opened Sunday, will debate a plan to establish a new type of lesser-trained hospital worker to provide some care to patients at bedside. <ORGANIZATION> AMA </ORGANIZATION> officials believe their plan for `` registered care technologists,'' who would handle such chores as changing bandages and taking vital signs, would be an innovative step toward easing the nation's nursing shortage. But the proposal has drawn harsh criticism from the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nurses </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ' </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>, which contends the best answer to the shortage is to improve working conditions and pay nurses better salaries. `` It's an impractical, poorly thought-out proposal,'' said <PERSON> Mary </PERSON> <PERSON> Foley </PERSON>, a nurse from <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION> and an elected Cabinet member for the nurses' association. `` It could be potentially very dangerous.'' She said nurses often help diagnose problems with patients and act as a backstop to doctors. The technogists would n't have the expertise to spot medical complications or other problems in a patient, she said. <PERSON> Lillian </PERSON> <PERSON> Joel </PERSON>, president of the <LOCATION> Kansas </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>, Mo.-based association representing 188,000 nurses, plans to testify against the proposal during a hearing Monday at the <ORGANIZATION> AMA </ORGANIZATION> convention. The <ORGANIZATION> Illinois </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nurses </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ' </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> also has organized a protest rally Monday morning. Dr. <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Hotchkiss </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> AMA </ORGANIZATION> president, disputed the nurses' concerns and contended the bedside technologists would give nurses more time to perform vital, highly technical patient-care management tasks `` It is in addition to nurses,'' <PERSON> Hotchkiss </PERSON> said. `` We are not threatening the nurses in any way. We want all the nurses we can get.'' Dr. <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> Painter </PERSON>, an internist from <LOCATION> Houston </LOCATION>, said the <ORGANIZATION> AMA </ORGANIZATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trustees </ORGANIZATION> devised the proposal because the nation's shortage of nurses is projected to hit 300,000 by `` We're dealing with a major shortage that does n't look like it will improve,'' Painter said. `` We do n't see this as a turf problem between medicine and nursing. ... Our view is the person who is really suffering from this acute shortage of bedside care is the patient.'' The <ORGANIZATION> AMA </ORGANIZATION> wants to test its idea on an experimental basis in states that now have the worst shortage of nurses, he said. The board's proposal would create three levels of `` registered care technologists.'' The first, an assistant technologist, would be a high school graduate who could begin working with patients after two months' training. The worker could become a full licensed technologist with an additional seven months' on-the-job training. With nine months of more specialized training, the worker would become an advanced technologist who could work in critical care units, Painter said. `` We thought it should be an apprentice-type training program,'' he said. `` We wanted to appeal to a different type of applicant who might not want to spend two to four years in college, but who would want to earn while they learn.'' But Ms. <PERSON> Foley </PERSON>, a nurse at <ORGANIZATION> St. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Francis </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Memorial </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hospital </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION>, called the proposal `` misguided.'' `` We do have a crisis right now because there is a shortage of nurses. But the solution to that is not to create an alternative health-care giver with lesser skills,'' she said. The proposal also has drawn criticism from within the <ORGANIZATION> AMA </ORGANIZATION> ranks. The <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION> delegation to the convention introduced a resolution to scrap the idea, contending it `` would further dilute the pool of available individuals for the nursing profession and would increase the cost of medical care by creating a new category of health care provider.'' Sunday was an opening session of the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Delegates </ORGANIZATION>, whose 420 members act as a policymaking legislature for the 295,000-member <ORGANIZATION> AMA </ORGANIZATION>. Dr. <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Hotchkiss </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Chesapeake </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Va. </LOCATION>, gave his farewell speech as outgoing president of the <ORGANIZATION> AMA </ORGANIZATION>, saying members must work to counter the attitude among a small number of doctors `` that the profession is no longer worth fighting for and ... is no longer worth pursuing as a career.'' <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Sammons </PERSON>, the <ORGANIZATION> AMA </ORGANIZATION>'s executive vice president, told the convention in a written report that doctors and scientists must be prepared to battle animal rights activists trying to ban the use of animals in medical research. `` I'm afraid that unless we undertake a massive effort to protect biomedical research ... these people are going to force medical science into a choice between experiments on animals and experiments on humans,'' <PERSON> Sammons </PERSON> said.
