<HEAD>LaserPhotos NY20, FX1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 Gay couples marched in matching colors, <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION>'s mayor brought his family, and balloons were released to memorialize AIDS deaths as half a million people participated in gay pride celebrations nationally Sunday. Police estimated 100,000 people marched down <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>'s Fifth Avenue, stopping for a period of silence as 10,000 balloons bearing messages and poems to people who have died of AIDS were released. Similar balloon releases occurred in <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hollywood </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif. </LOCATION> `` The balloons are symbolic of the freedom we, as homosexuals, have to fly free and be proud of what we are,'' said <PERSON> Kenn </PERSON> <PERSON> Kidd </PERSON>, an organizer. About 25 members of three organziations _ Jews for Morality, the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Coalition </ORGANIZATION> to Prevent the Spread of AIDS and the Committee for the <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> St. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Patrick </ORGANIZATION>'s _ protested opposite St. <PERSON> Patrick </PERSON>'s Cathedral, condemning homosexuals and shouting `` AIDS spreaders'' at parade participants In <LOCATION> Hartford </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Conn. </LOCATION>, about 600 gay activists chanting `` Gay bashing, we say no, homophobia's got to go,'' marched Saturday through downtown to the state Capitol. Activists attributed a bludgeoning death last month to anti-homosexual bias. <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>'s parade attracted several hundred marchers and many more spectators, and ended with a rally that attracted about 70,000, police said. A focus was support of a proposed human rights ordinance approved by a <ORGANIZATION> City </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> committee Thursday that would prohibit discrimination on the basis of age, martial status, disability or sexual orientation. Church groups have lobbied against it. <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> Mayor <PERSON> Eugene </PERSON> <PERSON> Sawyer </PERSON> was scheduled to speak at the rally but did n't show up. In <LOCATION> Seattle </LOCATION>, three congressional candidates turned out to court about 15,000 people who marched and rallied to cap a Lesbian and Gay Pride Week. In <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Art </PERSON> <PERSON> Agnos </PERSON> became the first mayor to take part in the city's annual Gay Freedom Day parade, which drew more than 160,000 marchers and spectators. <PERSON> Agnos </PERSON> rode with his family in a black 1931 <ORGANIZATION> Lincoln </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Continental </ORGANIZATION>. The parade also featured 175 floats and contingents, escorted by the group <PERSON> Dykes </PERSON> on Bikes, hundreds of leather-clad, motorcycle-revving lesbians. In addition to the traditional sprinkling of female impersonators and leather-clad, buttock-flashing cowboys, there were more serious contingents, such as Living Sober, a group of recovering drug addicts and alcoholics. In <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hollywood </LOCATION>, gay couples wearing matching colors strolled arm-in-arm along the parade route. Drill teams and marching bands entertained 150,000 people in the 19th annual Los Angeles Gay and Lesbian Pride Celebration. The parade grew somber as participants released 12,000 purple helium-filled balloons, each bearing the name of a person with AIDS. `` The AIDS crisis has brought together the gay and lesbian communities and has helped bring people out, not just to the festival, but to their families and their friends,'' said organizer <PERSON> Gary </PERSON> <PERSON> Jonker </PERSON>. `` I watched in 1982 and I do n't know if there was any AIDS groups present, said <PERSON> Gary </PERSON> <PERSON> Farnsworth </PERSON>, a student at <ORGANIZATION> City </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> College </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION>, watching the parade there. `` Then last year it seemed so heavy into AIDS, which is valid _ it's important. `` For all the thousands of people marching today in this parade, more than a thousand of them wo n't be here next year,'' he said. The AIDS-related concerns stem from the fatal virus' rampant spread through the male homosexual community. Nationally, 65,099 AIDS cases have been reported since June 1981, resulting in 36,874 deaths.
