<HEAD>One In Six Of Chicago's Public Housing Units Sit Vacant</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Nearly one out of every six public housing units in <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> sits vacant while tens of thousands of applicants wait for a place to live, a new study shows. <ORGANIZATION> Housing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Authority </ORGANIZATION> executive director <PERSON> Vincent </PERSON> <PERSON> Lane </PERSON> attributed the problem in part to street gangs who have taken over some of the buildings, frightening residents away. `` Decent people know when these guys are in a building. They try to get out. They move. When units become available in that building, nobody takes them,'' <PERSON> Lane </PERSON> said. In the past year, 1,550 of the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Housing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Authority </ORGANIZATION>'s 40,840 units, or more than four apartments a day, have become uninhabitable, the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tribune </ORGANIZATION> reported in Sunday editions A total of 6,218 units are vacant, according to the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sun-Times </ORGANIZATION>. At the <ORGANIZATION> Robert </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Taylor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Homes </ORGANIZATION> on the <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Side </LOCATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> Housing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Authority </ORGANIZATION>'s largest public housing project, gangs have `` taken over or have a foothold'' in half of the 56 buildings, <PERSON> Lane </PERSON> said. The vacancy rate has risen to 40 percent in some of the buildings controlled by gangs, compared with 6 percent at two <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Taylor </PERSON> buildings not dominated by gangs, he said. `` The problem is critical. The more vacancies you have, the more they proliferate. It's like a cancer eating away,'' said <PERSON> Lane </PERSON>. Cuts in funds, labor and equipment are also to blame for the problem, <PERSON> Lane </PERSON> and other officials said. But others blamed bureaucratic inefficiency. Former <ORGANIZATION> Housing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Authority </ORGANIZATION> board member <PERSON> Patricia </PERSON> <PERSON> Crowley </PERSON> contended that many of the 40,000 people on the waiting lists are dead or ca n't be located. The authority has cut its work force from 2,880 to 1,957 in the last year because of federal cutbacks, the <ORGANIZATION> Tribune </ORGANIZATION> said. So, instead of quickly repairing apartments when tenants move out, the authority boards up units, which are often run-down after years of abuse by tenants. But by boarding up the apartments, the authority is telling gangs `` that they can move in and do their number on it,'' <PERSON> Lane </PERSON> said.
