<HEAD>Montana-S.D. Fire Out of Control Again; Blazes Elsewhere Contained</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 5 grafs to UPDATE with fire again getting out of
control along Montana-South Dakota border, Idaho firefighters
controlling Tyndall Meadows blaze. Picks up 5th graf, `In Old ...'</NOTE>
<HEAD>By The Associated Press</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 A week-old fire along the <LOCATION> Montana-South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Dakota </LOCATION> border broke away from an army of more than 1,200 firefighters again Sunday and raced northward six or seven miles across thousands of acres of timber, officials reported. Officials were uncertain how many additional acres had burned, but their best estimate was that the fire covered more than 50,000 acres Sunday night in the <ORGANIZATION> Custer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Forest </ORGANIZATION>, said <PERSON> Jack </PERSON> <PERSON> Hendley </PERSON>, a spokesman at the <ORGANIZATION> Interagency </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fire </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> in Billings, <PERSON> Mont </PERSON>. Meantime, the number of widespread forest and brush fires continued to run far above average and to concern fire officials across the nation, though some fires were being brought under control. More than 700 acres of drought-seared grassland burned in <LOCATION> Southern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>. At least 10 people were injured _ one seriously enough to be hospitalized _ and four residences burned before firefighters controlled a 215-acre blaze Saturday in the high desert community of Apple Valley. Aided by overnight rainfall and cooler, humid weather, 200 <LOCATION> Idaho </LOCATION> firefighters controlled the 137-acre Tyndall Meadows fire in the <ORGANIZATION> Boise </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Forest </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sunday </ORGANIZATION> and planned to begin demobilizing Monday. In <LOCATION> Old </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Town </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Maine </LOCATION>, weekend rain also helped to remove the immediate threat of forest fires in some areas, but rangers said Sunday that rainfall was too light to make any difference in most of the state's northern woods. A fire that scorched at least 200 acres in the <LOCATION> Allagash </LOCATION> region of <LOCATION> Maine </LOCATION> was reported under control Sunday, but rangers said lightning posed a constant danger. In the western <LOCATION> Maine </LOCATION> woods, Assistant Regional <PERSON> Ranger </PERSON> <PERSON> Kenny </PERSON> <PERSON> Wing </PERSON> said Saturday's rain removed the danger for a couple of days. `` But with a little bit of sunshine and a little bit of wind, we'll be right back where we were,'' Wing said. Flames from the <LOCATION> Montana </LOCATION> fire came within 300 yards of a ranch near the <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Dakota </LOCATION> border Saturday night before firefighters and air-dropped flame retardant turned the blaze away, officials said. `` It was very extreme, a pretty tense situation,'' said fire information officer <PERSON> Michelle </PERSON> <PERSON> Ravnikar </PERSON>. Fire had burned 39,680 acres as of Sunday morning. So far, firefighting costs have topped $ 900,000 and are expected to reach $ 1.75 million, and timber losses are predicted at $ 2.5 million. The <ORGANIZATION> Maine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Forest </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> reported 10 to 15 new fires a day last week, compared with the usual two or three a day in June. As of late last week, 556 fires had burned more than 2,200 acres this year in <LOCATION> Maine </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Louisiana </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Forestry </ORGANIZATION> firefighters normally battle about 100 fires during June, but so far this month 511 fires have been reported. Approximately eight times as many acres of land have been lost this month as in June 1987. High temperatures, consistently low humidity and windy days have combined to make conditions excellent for fires and only a long, steady rain will make things better, officials said.
