<FIRST>r f AM-WallStreet-Profits     06-26 0346</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Wall Street-Profits,0357</SECOND>
<HEAD>Survey: First Quarter Industry Profit Concentrated In 10
Investment Banks</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Ten big investment banks accounted for 43 percent of the securities industry's first quarter profit, indicating the impact of the October market crash still is being felt by most <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> firms, an industry trade group has reported. The industry posted a pre-tax profit of $ 1.1 billion in the first quarter, compared with a $ 2.1 billion loss in fourth quarter 1987 and a $ 2 billion pre-tax profit for all of last year, the <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Industry </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> said in a survey released Monday. Big investment banks constituting 2.5 percent of the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> member firms accounted for more than 43 of the industry-wide profit, while just 23 percent of the <ORGANIZATION> NYSE </ORGANIZATION> firms accounted for 61 percent of the profit, <ORGANIZATION> SIA </ORGANIZATION> stated. The figures indicated the ripples from the October crash still were being felt mostly by the retail sector, where the bulk of the nation's securities firms are focused, said <ORGANIZATION> SIA </ORGANIZATION> president, <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> I. </PERSON> <PERSON> O'Brien </PERSON>. Industry-wide commission revenue fell by 25 percent, to $ 2.4 billion from $ 3.2 billion in the fourth quarter, for the worst quarterly shjowing since fourth quarter 1985. Mutual fund revenue rose to $ 430 million in the first quarter from $ 360 million in the previous three months, although it was below the 1987 quarterly average of $ 552 million, <ORGANIZATION> SIA </ORGANIZATION> reported. At the same time, industry-wide trading profit surged 63 percent higher, to $ 3.1 billion from $ 1.9 billion in fourth quarter 1987, while investment profit fell to $ 828 million from $ 1.3 billion in the fourth quarter, but remained far over the 1987 quarterly average of $ 17 million. Revenue related to other activitites such as mergers and acquisitions and private stock placements nearly equaled the $ 2.9 billion quarterly average for 1987, the report stated. Those results indicate firms concentrating in investment banking and trading continued to do well, `` while the retail hemisphere has almost ground to a halt,'' the <ORGANIZATION> SIA </ORGANIZATION> stated. The report was included in the group's `` Trends'' publication, which is issued several times a year.
</TEXT>
