<HEAD>Foreign Ministers Look For Solutions To Foreign Debt Problem</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New throughout to UPDATE with Sunday communique. No pickup.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By SERGIO CARRASCO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>OAXACA, Mexico (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The foreign ministers of seven leading Latin American nations stated Sunday that the $ 8 billion in outstanding mutual debt among their nations was the main obstacle to creating a regional common market. Foreign ministers of the Group of Eight _ <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Argentina </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Venezuela </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Colombia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Uruguay </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Peru </LOCATION> _ issued a communique at the end of their weekend meeting saying they agreed to work together to find a solution to the problem. Group member <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> was absent from the meeting. <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> was suspended from the group at its last meeting in February, shortly after military leader Gen. <PERSON> Manuel </PERSON> <PERSON> Antonio </PERSON> <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON> was indicted in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> on drug trafficking charges. <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON> engineered the ouster of President <PERSON> Eric </PERSON> <PERSON> Arturo </PERSON> <PERSON> Delvalle </PERSON> after <PERSON> Delvalle </PERSON> tried to fire him. The ministers, who also spent much of their time working on an agenda for a summit meeting of their presidents later this year, offered no specifics about that meeting. Latin American leaders have talked of a common market for years, but earlier attempts at economic integration have failed. In the 1960s, a Central American Common Market and an 11-nation Latin American Free Trade Association were formed but later broke apart amid civil wars and squabbling over tariffs. Recently, the Group of Eight has been trying to revive the plan, spurned on the economic stagnation blamed in part on the region's massive foreign debts Last year, for example, <LOCATION> Argentina </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Uruguay </LOCATION> signed accords breaking down trade barriers. `` It is necessary to create mechanisms that will allow the nations of <LOCATION> Latin </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> to develop in the medium - and long-term,'' said <ORGANIZATION> Mexican </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Foreign </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Victor </PERSON> <PERSON> Flores </PERSON> <PERSON> Olea </PERSON> The ministers also agreed that Latin American nations should take the `` most concerted position possible'' in confronting their international lenders. On Monday, the ministers will meet in <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>, turning their attention to the problems of <LOCATION> Central </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION>'s status in the group They are to meet with President <PERSON> Miguel </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> la </PERSON> <PERSON> Madrid </PERSON> and with <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION>'s foreign minister, <PERSON> Jorge </PERSON> <PERSON> Ritter </PERSON>.
</TEXT>
