<HEAD>Sense and Nonsense in the Stock Market</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: This is for Monday PMs. John Cunniff is on vacation.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By CHET CURRIER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 New evidence has come in lately to buttress the widely espoused belief that the stock market makes no sense. On May 17, the government reported a sharp drop in the trade deficit and the Dow Jones average of 30 industrials fell 21.22 points. On June 14, the government reported another sharp drop in the trade deficit and the Dow Jones average of 30 industrials rose 25.07 points. At least one large bank ran advertisements noting these divergent performances, and suggested its certificates of deposit as an alternative to stocks for people who wanted investments they could understand. The bank had a point. Any investor with a strong desire for order, simplicity and stability is probably better off avoiding any strategy that depends on the day-to-day fluctuations of the stock market. But to the charge that the market behaves irrationally, its advocates respectfully plead innocent. Though the reasoning may get convoluted at times, they say, there is almost always a method behind the madness portrayed on the ticker tape. In the case of the recent trade reports, said <PERSON> Hugh </PERSON> <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON>, an analyst at <ORGANIZATION> First </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Albany </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Albany </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.Y. </LOCATION>, the explanation for the market's differing responses lay not far below the surface. `` In both instances,'' he noted, `` the trade deficit declined significantly. `` However, the decline in the March deficit -LRB- reported in May -RRB- signaled that the economy may be strengthening, and the decline in the April deficit -LRB- reported in June -RRB- signaled that the economy may be weakening. `` The March trade deficit improved because exports surged, suggesting that domestic demand in <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>, etc., was strengthening and was placing pressure on <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> manufacturers to meet that demand. `` This was viewed by the financial markets as inflationary. `` The April trade deficit improved because imports declined, suggesting that domestic demand in the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> was slowing. This suggested inflation may not be as big a problem as it has been made out to be. `` The two events, when taken together and reviewed along with the market's reaction to other recent releases, demonstrate how important it is to the financial markets that the economy slows down from the pace of the prior three quarters.'' In other words, stock traders' reactions to the trade reports were simply a new variation on a theme that has become familiar on Wall Street in the 1980s: `` Good news is bad news,'' and vice versa. Favorable news for near-term business activity conjures up images of increased inflation, rising interest rates and credit-tightening by the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION>, all of which could serve as prelude to a recession. Unfavorable news for near-term business activity evokes visions of reduced inflation, falling interest rates and stimulative credit policy from the <ORGANIZATION> Fed </ORGANIZATION>, all of which could set the stage for renewed growth later on. Suppose you have worked your way through all this and you still do n't buy it. How could one monthly report on a single aspect of the economy send fears of inflation rippling through the market, and another four weeks later persuade thousands of investors that things were not so bad after all? Well, one could argue, expectations do not really change that radically. When the market rises or falls 20 points as measured by the <ORGANIZATION> Dow </ORGANIZATION>, it is actually moving up or down by about 1 percent to adjust for the latest information received. And at the same time, one could acknowledge that this `` adjustment'' process is emotional, messy and sometimes outright violent. Most devotees of the stock market will readily admit to all that. Just do n't try to tell them it is nonsensical.
</TEXT>
